"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388121","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-15","<p>The department’s spend on newspapers and periodicals for the calendar year 2014 (Jan-Dec) was £49,886.69. This compares to £189,650 in 2009/10.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Detailed information on the periodicals and newspapers to which the department subscribes is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-15T15:10:38.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388121/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388121/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-07","Treasury: Press","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which periodicals and newspapers his Department subscribes to; what quantity of each such periodical is so obtained; and what the cost of such subscriptions was in 2014.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","6034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388122","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>As housing is a devolved matter, this change will apply to England and it will be for the devolved administrations to take their decisions as to whether they would wish to apply a similar requirement in their areas.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-13T14:55:51.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388122/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388122/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Social Rented Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the proposed four-year residency requirement for EU citizens to access social housing is intended to apply throughout the UK.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388123","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-14","<p>The information held by the Department on the proportion of Discretionary Housing Payment funding spent and returned by each local authority and the average amount of funding returned in the last three years is provided in the table which I will place in the House library.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-07-14T13:54:15.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388123/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388123/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-07","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on (a) the proportion of Discretionary Housing Payment funding spent by each local authority, (b) how many and which local authorities returned such funding allocated to them, (c) how much funding each such local authority returned and (d) what the average amount of such funding was which was returned in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","6049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388124","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>This Government is committed to increasing housing supply and home ownership. We have already made progress - housing completions in the quarter to March 2015 are up 21% on the same quarter in the previous year; starts on new homes in the year to March 2015 totalled 140,500, the highest annual total since 2007; and planning permissions were granted for 261,000 homes in the year to March 2015 – but there is more to be done.<br><br>This year we will introduce a Housing Bill to unlock brownfield land to build new homes; provide the framework to deliver starter homes and extend Right to Buy to housing association tenants.<br><br>We will help builders to build: Public sector land has already been released to deliver over 109,000 new homes and over 100,000 homes have been supported through the £1.3 billion Large Sites programme. Over this Parliament we have ambitions to release public sector land for 150,000 homes; kick-start development in 20 Housing Zones outside London, which with 8 other shortlisted sites has the potential to deliver up to 45,000 new homes; create a £1 billion Brownfield Fund; and provide capacity funding to support the development of new garden settlements. We will support small and medium sized enterprises through the Builders’ Finance Fund (2015-17) and the £100 million Housing Growth Partnership with Lloyds Bank. We want to double the number of custom and self-built homes through ‘Right to Build’ and a £150 million fund for serviced plots.<br><br>Nearly 2 million households have been helped to realise aspirations to own their homes through Government-backed schemes. This Government will build 200,000 Starter Homes exclusively for first-time buyers under 40 years old, at a minimum of 20 per cent below open market value; extend Help to Buy Mortgages to 2020; and introduce a Help to Buy ISA to help people save for a deposit. Finally, we will give more people the chance to own their home by extending Right to Buy discounts to tenants of housing associations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-13T14:13:45.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388124/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388124/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he has taken to increase house building by 2030.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","6003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388125","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>Estimates on the number of households that would be affected by the policy was published in Annex A of the summary of responses to consultation document in 2013 which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225313/High_Income_Social_Tenants_-_Pay_to_stay.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225313/High_Income_Social_Tenants_-_Pay_to_stay.pdf</a>.<br><br></p><p>We do not collect information on additional rent collected.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5998","2015-07-13T14:19:03.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388125/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388125/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of social housing tenants required to pay higher rent under the Pay to Stay scheme in each year since that policy was introduced.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","5997"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388126","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>Estimates on the number of households that would be affected by the policy was published in Annex A of the summary of responses to consultation document in 2013 which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225313/High_Income_Social_Tenants_-_Pay_to_stay.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225313/High_Income_Social_Tenants_-_Pay_to_stay.pdf</a>.<br><br></p><p>We do not collect information on additional rent collected.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5997","2015-07-13T14:19:03.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388126/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388126/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much additional rent has been collected in each year since the Pay to Stay policy was introduced.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","5998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388127","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-13","<p>Compensation arrangements are already provided through The Gas (Street Works) (Compensation of Small Businesses) Regulations 1996 and the Water Industry Act 1991, which provide for compensation to be paid in certain circumstances in respect of loss or damage caused by gas-related and water-related street works. More widely, we are taking steps to reduce the disruption caused by street works, including the wider application of permit schemes and the piloting of lane rental. Further information about these initiatives may be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.dft.gov.uk/topics/road-management/street-works/" target="_blank">www.dft.gov.uk/topics/road-management/street-works</a></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p /><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-13T10:34:16.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388127/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388127/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-07","Road Works: Retail Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to support high street retailers that have incurred significant losses due to overrunning street works.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","5857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388128","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>Section 106 planning obligations and the Community Infrastructure Levy provide separate mechanisms for securing developer contributions to infrastructure such as roads, schools, flood defences, health and sporting facilities. Local authorities decide how these contributions and receipts are spent , based on local circumstances andthe views of the community, and this information is held locally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5942","2015-07-13T15:32:12.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388128/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388128/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Community Infrastructure Levy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will introduce legislative proposals for a statutory requirement for local authorities to give priority to provision of local sporting facilities when considering how best to utilise section 106 community infrastructure levy payments from developers.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","5939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388129","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-15","The Department for Communities and Local Government does not hold this information.","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-15T14:37:26.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388129/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388129/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Playing Fields","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the number of local community cricket and rugby pitches in (a) England, (b) East Sussex and (c) Wealden constituency that have (i) been sold for redevelopment and (ii) stopped being used for that purpose for other reasons in the (A) five, (B) 10 and (c) 15 years.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","5941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388130","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>Section 106 planning obligations and the Community Infrastructure Levy provide separate mechanisms for securing developer contributions to infrastructure such as roads, schools, flood defences, health and sporting facilities. Local authorities decide how these contributions and receipts are spent , based on local circumstances andthe views of the community, and this information is held locally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5939","2015-07-13T15:32:12.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388130/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388130/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Community Infrastructure Levy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of section 106 community infrastructure levy payments in (a) England, (b) East Sussex and (c) Wealden constituency have been directed to provision of sporting facilities in each of the last (i) five, (ii) 10 and (iii) 15 years.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","5942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388131","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>We do not hold this information at parliamentary constituency level.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5836","2015-07-13T14:19:53.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388131/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388131/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and what proportion of households in social housing in each parliamentary constituency outside London have an annual income above £30,000.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","5802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388132","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-15","<p>Managing agents must comply with the obligations in the lease, and must comply with landlord and tenant legislation. This sets out a framework of rights and protections for leaseholders, and also places particular obligations on landlords, and managing agents acting on their behalf. <br><br>This includes providing information about service charges where a written request is made. Managing agents should also comply with two Codes of Practice approved by the Secretary of State for the management of residential leasehold property.<br><br>Since 1 October 2014 managing agents have also been required to belong to one of three Government approved redress schemes, to whom leaseholders can take a complaint. <br><br>We continue to consider ways to improve transparency in the residential leasehold sector without adding disproportionate burdens and costs.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-15T14:25:00.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388132/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388132/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to enhance the transparency of the operation and financial performance of management companies for housing.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","5783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388133","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>We do not hold this information at parliamentary constituency level.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5802","2015-07-13T14:19:53.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388133/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388133/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-07","Social Rented Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and what proportion of households in social housing in each parliamentary constituency in London have an annual income above £40,000.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","5836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388134","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>Between 2014 and 2016, over £118,000 will have been invested by British Cycling and Calderdale council to get more people cycling in Calderdale. Calderdale is also part of the West Yorkshire Tour de France legacy, which is working with partners from sport, transport and health to get more people cycling in the local area. Further, in February 2015, the Government committed further funding to British Cycling to improve facilities in Yorkshire.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-23T16:56:00.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388134/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388134/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Cycling: Calderdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to promote cycling as a recreational activity in Calderdale.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","5761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388135","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-14","<p>The full text of the agreement reached between the BBC and the government on funding of the over-75s free television licences has been published on the Gov.uk website, and can be found using the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443735/Letter_from_George_Osborne_and_John_Whittingdale_to_Tony_Hall_FINAL.PDF" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443735/Letter_from_George_Osborne_and_John_Whittingdale_to_Tony_Hall_FINAL.PDF</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-14T14:29:20.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388135/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388135/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will publish the full text of the agreement he reached with the BBC that the BBC will fund the provision of TV Licences for those age over 75, announced on 6 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388136","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-14","<p>The financial assessment of the impact on the public purse of the agreement with the BBC to take on responsibility for funding over-75s free television licences announced on 6 July 2015 has been published in the Office For Budget Responsibility’s Economic and Fiscal Outlook, July 2015. Tables 4.13 and 4.14 on pages 110 and 111 and paragraphs 4.128 and 4.129 on page 136 detail changes in the BBC’s expenditure since the March 2015 forecast. The information can be found using the following link: <a href="http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.independent.gov.uk/July-2015-EFO-234224.pdf" target="_blank">http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.independent.gov.uk/July-2015-EFO-234224.pdf</a>. The impact on the Exchequer has been published in the Summer Budget 2015: policy costings document, on page 61 of the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443195/Policy_costings_summer_budget_2015.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443195/Policy_costings_summer_budget_2015.pdf</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-14T14:28:26.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388136/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388136/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will publish a financial assessment of the effect on the public purse and the BBC agreement announced on 6 July 2015 that the BBC will fund the provision of TV Licences for those age over 75.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388137","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>High stakes gambling’ is a relative term and may be open to different interpretation. The Gambling Act 2005 and associated regulations establish the types and levels of gambling permitted in a range of licensed environments and the controls required to be put in place to keep that gambling fair and safe for all.</p><p> </p><p>Regardless of the level of stakes, the Gambling Commission requires all operators providing facilities for gambling to adhere to the licence conditions and codes of practice relevant to their activity designed to minimise harm generated by gambling.</p><p> </p><p>Under the 2005 Act fixed odds betting terminals are permitted in casinos and bookmakers. High street betting shops are limited to four machines per premises. The Act also set the current gaming machine entitlements for casinos.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recently introduced new regulations in April which ended unsupervised stakes above £50 on FOBTs in betting shops. We will want to assess the impact of these measures before we consider any further legislative options.</p><p><br>Any discussion about changes to gaming machine entitlements in casinos would need to be accompanied by robust proposals from the industry for managing any additional risk of harm to players that may arise.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-07-23T12:37:30.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388137/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388137/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will take steps to ensure that (a) high stakes gambling takes place only in (i) casinos and (ii) other highly supervised premises, (b) Fixed Odds Betting Terminals are not located in bookmakers and (c) casinos have more appropriate numbers of slot machines.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","5799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388138","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>Correspondence on the agreement has been published on the BBC’s website and the BBC Trust's website (here: <a href="http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/tony-hall-letter-coe-sscms.pdf" target="_blank">http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/tony-hall-letter-coe-sscms.pdf</a>; <a href="http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbctrust/news/press_releases/2015/chancellor_sos" target="_blank">http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbctrust/news/press_releases/2015/chancellor_sos</a>).</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-23T17:02:22.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388138/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388138/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will publish all correspondence he has had with the BBC on the agreement announced on 6 July 2015 that the BBC will fund the provision of television licences for those aged over 75.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388139","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>The Government, BBC and commercial radio are jointly funding the long term expansion of the local DAB network across the UK with the building of 182 new digital transmitters and modifications and frequency changes at a further 49 sites by the end of September 2016. Ofcom has published detailed maps outlining the improvements to coverage in local areas across the UK. As a result of this new investment, according to Ofcom, it is expected that local DAB coverage in Wales will increase from 63% to 85.4% of households and from 46.7% to 66.3% of major roads.</p><p> </p><p>Separately the BBC is rolling out its national DAB network to a further 162 transmitter sites across the UK by the end of 2015<strong>. </strong>This programme will increase the coverage of its DAB network in Wales from 86% to 92% of homes.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-23T17:00:38.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388139/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388139/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Digital Broadcasting: Radio","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the quality of DAB radio coverage in Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","5818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388140","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-29","<p>Ensuring there is competitive broadband market is a matter for Ofcom, although the Government has a keen interest in an efficient and effective market, capable of delivering users the level of service they require. Ofcom regularly monitors and regulates competition in electronic communications markets through market reviews. In June 2014 Ofcom published a Statement on its Fixed Access Market Reviews 2014 and announced a number of changes designed to promote competition in the markets. The Regulator also announced in March this year a Strategic Review of Digital Communications in the UK, in order to assess future issues around infrastructure and competition.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-29T15:39:14.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388140/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388140/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Broadband: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to ensure competition between broadband infrastructure providers.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","5784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388141","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-22","<p>Sport England does not hold the demographic data for national sports governing body members. However, the organisation Women in Sport collects data regarding the executive board members of national sports governing bodies and the proportion who are female in their regular report ‘Trophy Women’. When the first report was published in 2009, 20% of board members across NGBs were female and one quarter of NGBs had no women in their board positions. The most recent figures shown an improvement – in 2014 27% of board members across NGBs are female and the number of NGBs with no women in board positions has reduced to 3.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-07-22T12:13:33.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388141/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388141/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Sports: Governing Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of members of national sports governing bodies are women.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388142","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>This Government continues to prioritise actions to improve children's safety online. Under the auspices of the UK Council for Child Internet Safety (UKCCIS), Government meets key partners on a quarterly basis to drive and oversee progress.</p><p> </p><p>In the Autumn, Ofcom will report on progress made by BT, Sky, Talk Talk and Virgin to roll-out family friendly filters. These four ISPs provide internet services to around 90% of the UK's fixed-line customers. Ofcom has already delivered three reports on progress in this area, and will be delivering a final report later this year. Whilst we await Ofcom's findings, we understand from the ISPs that collectively, over 95% of customers have now made an active choice on filters, or had filters applied to their accounts.</p><p> </p><p>We estimate that around 90% of public wifi is provided by six providers, all of whom apply filters which block adult content and illegal child sexual abuse material by default in areas that children are likely to be unsupervised by a parent. The recently-established UKCCIS Filters Group, which evolved out of a previous group dedicated to overblocking, will keep Government informed as to progress in this area, and is continuing to look into ways to address concerns about over-blocking.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","5788","2015-07-23T16:58:58.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388142/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388142/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress he is making on steps to ensure that internet service providers are (a) meeting commitments to deliver unavoidable choice to parents on setting network level filters at home, (b) providing family-friendly wifi in public places and (c) tackling concerns about over-blocking.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388143","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-14","<p>The full text of the agreement reached between the BBC and the government on funding of the over-75s free television licences has been published on the Gov.uk website, and can be found using the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443735/Letter_from_George_Osborne_and_John_Whittingdale_to_Tony_Hall_FINAL.PDF" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443735/Letter_from_George_Osborne_and_John_Whittingdale_to_Tony_Hall_FINAL.PDF</a></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-14T14:34:05.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388143/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388143/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","BBC Trust: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will publish the letter he sent to the BBC Trust on 3 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388144","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>62 MHz of spectrum under 5 GHz has been already released. Ofcom expects to auction up to 190 MHz of additional spectrum at 2.3 GHz and 3.4 GHz in this financial year.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-23T17:00:00.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388144/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388144/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Radio Frequencies: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much spectrum below 5GHz has been released since 2010.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388145","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-14","<p>This is a matter for the communications regulator, Ofcom, or the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA), either of which might review the fixed line telecommunications market on their own initiative. Ofcom could conduct a market study and, if its findings warranted it, refer it to the CMA for a market investigation. In theory it is possible for the Secretary of State to request a referral to the CMA under Section 131 (1) of the Enterprise Act. However, this is a ‘reserve power’ and has never been used.</p><p>Ofcom periodically reviews the telecommunications fixed access market, most recently in May 2014. In March this year Ofcom launched an overarching Strategic Review of Digital Communications in the UK. This is covering both fixed and wireless networks and services.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-14T14:30:59.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388145/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388145/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Telecommunications: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to refer fixed line telecommunications services to the Competition and Markets Authority.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","5787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388146","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>This Government continues to prioritise actions to improve children's safety online. Under the auspices of the UK Council for Child Internet Safety (UKCCIS), Government meets key partners on a quarterly basis to drive and oversee progress.</p><p> </p><p>In the Autumn, Ofcom will report on progress made by BT, Sky, Talk Talk and Virgin to roll-out family friendly filters. These four ISPs provide internet services to around 90% of the UK's fixed-line customers. Ofcom has already delivered three reports on progress in this area, and will be delivering a final report later this year. Whilst we await Ofcom's findings, we understand from the ISPs that collectively, over 95% of customers have now made an active choice on filters, or had filters applied to their accounts.</p><p> </p><p>We estimate that around 90% of public wifi is provided by six providers, all of whom apply filters which block adult content and illegal child sexual abuse material by default in areas that children are likely to be unsupervised by a parent. The recently-established UKCCIS Filters Group, which evolved out of a previous group dedicated to overblocking, will keep Government informed as to progress in this area, and is continuing to look into ways to address concerns about over-blocking.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","5790","2015-07-23T16:58:58.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388146/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388146/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of internet customers have made an active choice on filters.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388147","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>I intend to lay the LRO later this year.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-07-23T12:38:35.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388147/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388147/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Lotteries: Exemptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will introduce the Exempt Lotteries Legislative Reform Order in 2015.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","5789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388148","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>Digital skills provision in maintained schools, taught within the computing curriculum, is funded through the Dedicated Schools Grant (DSG) which is the responsibility of the Department for Education. Public funding for digital skills in Further Education and Skills and Higher Education is the responsibility of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Education and Department for Business, Innovation and Skills regularly speaks to Her Majesty’s Treasury about all aspects of funding for schools, Higher and Further Education.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-23T16:57:14.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388148/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388148/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Digital Technology: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on funding for digital skills.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","5773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388149","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>Having safe and better sporting facilities can make a significant difference in getting more women active. Sport England invests to improve the quality and features of all types of facilities, from small local clubs to major projects. Between 2013 and 2017 its total investment in facilities will be over £300 million.</p><p>Sport England’s experience has shown that the quality of changing facilities has a significant impact on women and girls’ inclination to play sport. In the last round of its Inspired Facilities fund (Round 7) Sport England invested £2.7 million to help local sports clubs upgrade and improve their changing facilities.</p><p>Sport England has a statutory planning role which means it has to be consulted on all planning applications that affect playing fields.</p><p>In 2012/13, 94 per cent of the applications resulted in the places where people play sport being improved or safeguarded. (Published in December 2014, these are the most recent figures available, due to the length of time individual planning processes can take to complete.)</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-07-23T12:36:27.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388149/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388149/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Sports: Facilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to promote the provision of local sporting facilities for (a) women and (b) general use.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","5943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388150","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-08-04","<p>Wimbledon is the world's most popular Tennis event, organised by the AELTC closely in conjunction with the LTA, who do all they can to minimise delays for spectators and to make the experience of this wonderful event as enjoyable as possible. DCMS holds regular meetings with NGBs and are assured that the LTA takes the spectator experience very seriously and continually explore what more can be done to improve spectator experience for future tournaments.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-08-04T09:00:29.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388150/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388150/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Tennis: Wimbledon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will request the Lawn Tennis Association to take steps to reduce queue waiting times at Wimbledon.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","5852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388151","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-13","<p>Following the Secretary of State's announcement on 1 July, which launched the ballot website to strong press interest, we are looking at a number of further opportunities to raise awareness of the ballot. Leaflets were handed to all those attending the 1 July event this year and are available at the Thiepval Visitor Centre. Our partner organisations, The Royal British Legion and the Commonwealth War Graves Commission, are also promoting the information on their websites and through related social media channels.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Communications activity will focus on key points in the period from now until the ballot closes on 18 November. It will involve press announcements and planned coverage in both media and broadcast outlets to highlight the relevance of the battle of the Somme, the upcoming centenary and the ballot arrangements. The communications campaign will be supported by a strong social media presence, under #Somme100, to promote engagement beyond traditional audiences and direct users to the dedicated event website. We will also work closely with our key stakeholders to amplify messaging around the ballot and look to use celebrity endorsement.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-07-13T14:12:25.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388151/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388151/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","World War I: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to publicise the ballot for 8,000 free tickets to the ceremony to mark the centenary of the Battle of the Somme in July 2016.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","6009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388152","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>The policy for continuation of free television licences for over-75s is set out in the published government and BBC agreement, which says that, at the BBC’s request, the BBC will take responsibility for the policy following this Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-23T17:01:34.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388152/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388152/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether the BBC has undertaken that free TV licences for over-75s will continue beyond 2020.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388153","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-14","<p>My Department does not generally record expenditure by constituency and this information could only be provided at disproportionate cost. However, it is possible to state the amounts paid to churches in Ashfield under the Listed Places of Worship grant scheme, which are as follows.</p><p>Year to 31 March</p><p>2015 10,340.20</p><p>2014 347.95</p><p>2013 43,921.29</p><p>2012 449.35</p><p>2011 3,095.13</p><p> </p><p>Total £58,153.92</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-14T14:26:46.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388153/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388153/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Ashfield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how much his Department has spent under each budget sub-head in Ashfield constituency in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","5873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388154","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-14","<p>DCMS will be consulting on a new strategy over the summer and will publish our new approach later this year. As sport extends across almost every area of government activity, this strategy needs to be cross-Government to be effective. With this in mind, DCMS ministers have already met with ministerial colleagues from a range of departments to build on the positive work already underway. We will continue to engage with them to develop the strategy.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-07-14T16:27:03.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388154/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388154/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-07","Sports: Departmental Coordination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what meetings he has had with Ministers in other Departments to discuss the development of cross-departmental sport-based initiatives.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","6033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388155","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-15","<p>I have made no such assessment.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-15T15:08:26.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388155/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388155/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","USA: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the safety of US government procedures for transporting and maintaining nuclear missiles in considering whether to permit such missiles to be based in the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388156","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-14","<p>Permission must be sought in advance of any operation launched from a UK base and must satisfy our legal requirements, but it is not our general policy to give information on the detail of operations conducted by other nations.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-14T15:22:08.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388156/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388156/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","USA: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the US has sought permission from his Department to use US bases in the UK in connection with airstrikes in (a) Libya, (b) any other country in North Africa and (c) Yemen.","true","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","6032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388157","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-13","<p>The number of trail hunts that have taken place on Ministry of Defence land in each hunting season (September until April) since 2008-09 is shown below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Hunting Season</strong></p><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Trail Hunts</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09</p></td><td><p>222</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10</p></td><td><p>132</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>230</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>156</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1012-13</p></td><td><p>208</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>248</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>160<strong>*</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>*</strong>Not all information for the 2014-15 season is currently available.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-07-13T16:30:38.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388157/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388157/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2015 to Question 5458, how many trail hunts have taken place on his Department's land for each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","5988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388158","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) continues to support the Bahrain Defence Force in the agreement to improve facilities at the Mina Salman Port in Bahrain. This process is led and owned by Bahrain. The MOD will continue to provide support and advice when required for this project, as part of our partnership with Bahrain.</p><p>The agreement with Bahrain will provide a permanent base for UK mine hunters and it will support other Royal Navy and Royal Fleet Auxiliary vessels in the Gulf region. The enhanced facilities will provide better support for ships on operations, equipment storage and multi-purpose accommodation for Service personnel.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-13T16:20:39.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388158/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388158/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Bahrain: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent representations have been received by his Department on plans to build a permanent UK naval base in Bahrain.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388159","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-13","<p>In addition to UK personnel wholly providing support for British-supplied equipment, we have a small number of liaison personnel in Saudi coalition Headquarters, including the Maritime Coalition Co-ordination Centre that supports the enablement of humanatarian aid into Yemen. There are no UK aircraft or training in direct support of Saudi operations. We continue to supply equipment that conforms to our export criteria.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-07-13T16:22:26.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388159/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388159/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government is assisting the Saudi-led offensive in Yemen by the provision of (a) personnel, (b) aircraft, (c) training and (d) any other type of support.","true","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","6002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388160","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Ministry of Defence is focused on fully supporting the Cabinet Office-led Strategic Defence and Security Review (SDSR) as a key priority. Information on the total number of officials working on the SDSR across Government is not held.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-07-13T16:21:09.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388160/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388160/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Strategic Defence and Security Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many officials are working (a) in his Department and (b) across Government on the Strategic Defence and Security Review.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","6006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388161","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-13","<p>The following table shows the number of Service personnel who were made redundant in each specified year who were subsequently re-employed by the Ministry of Defence.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of Service Personnel made Redundant (see note 1)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,700</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,470</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>4,280</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,350</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of Redundant Service Personnel who have since been re-employed (see note 2)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>110</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>320</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>470</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>120</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note 1 - Service personnel excludes Full Time Reservists personnel, Gurkhas, Naval activated Reservists, mobilised Reservists, Military Provost Guard Service and Non Regular Permanent Staff.</p><p> </p><p>Note 2 - Figures have been rounded to the nearest 10, though numbers ending in “5” have been rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to prevent systematic bias.</p><p> </p><p>The number re-employed refer to Service personnel who left the UK Regular Forces on redundancy and have since been re-employed as a UK Regular, Reservist, or MOD Civil Servant.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-07-13T16:23:28.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388161/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388161/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Armed Forces: Re-employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many service personnel made redundant in each year since 2010 his Department has re-employed.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","5995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388162","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Ministry of Defence only holds relevant information on the Joint Personnel Administration (JPA) system dating from April 2007. The following table therefore shows the number of Armed Forces personnel who, having left their Service since April 2007, were subsequently re-employed by the Department in each requested year.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial </strong></p><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Number of Service Personnel who left service who have since been </strong></p><p><strong>re-employed (see note 1)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,740</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1,810</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,040</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,680</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,740</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note 1 – Service personnel excludes Full Time Reserve Service personnel and reservists.</p><p>Note 2 – Figures prior to Financial Year 2013/14 are reported as estimates due to a change in methodology used to identify personnel who were re-employed to the Reserves.</p><p>Note 3 - Figures have been rounded to the nearest 10, though numbers ending in “5” have been rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to prevent systematic bias.</p><p> </p><p>The number re-employed refer to Service personnel who left the UK Regular Forces and have since been re-employed as a UK Regular, Reservist, or MOD Civil Servant.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-07-13T16:31:15.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388162/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388162/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Veterans: Re-employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many former members of the armed forces his Department has re-employed in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","5996"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388163","Ministry of Defence","true","2015-07-13","<p>To date, the Royal Navy has rescued <del class="ministerial">4,752</del> <ins class="ministerial">4,747</ins> persons under its Search and Rescue mission in the Mediterranean. The Royal Navy does not record whether a rescued person is a refugee or an economic migrant; this is the responsibility of the receiving nation (in this instance, Italy). The Ministry of Defence does not hold overall statistics of all those rescued at sea by other nations.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-13T16:24:35.25Z","2015-07-23T11:40:32.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388163/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388163/answer","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388163/answer/previousversion/13486","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many refugees the Royal Navy has rescued in the Mediterranean (a) in total and (b) as a proportion of all those rescued.","false","Biography information for Mr Philip Hollobone","Kettering","Mr Philip Hollobone","6011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388164","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-14","<p>I can confirm that, following consideration of any operational sensitivities for the UK or partners, we will consult with the US Navy on the potential placement of a redacted version of this report in the Library.</p><p>No decisions have yet been taken by the Government on a wider post-Afghanistan review. We remain focused on supporting the National Unity Government of Afghanistan as part of NATO's Resolute Support Mission.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-14T15:20:52.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388164/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388164/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Afghanistan: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 1 June 2015 to Question 160 on Afghanistan: armed conflict, if his Department will seek permission from partners to place the report in the Library, redacted as necessary; and whether his Department has commissioned or undertaken any other post-Afghanistan review.","true","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","5927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388165","Department for Education","false","2015-07-13","<p>The main eligibility criterion for the pupil premium is whether a pupil aged 4-16 has been registered for free school meals (FSM) at any point in the last 6 years.</p><p> </p><p>FSM eligibility captures both non-working families and families working for less than 16 hours per week, and this is based on a parent being in receipt of particular benefits, such as: income-based Jobseekers Allowance; income-related Employment and Support Allowance; Child Tax Credit, provided they have an annual gross income of no more than £16,190 and are not also entitled to Working Tax Credit; and Working Tax Credit run-on, paid for four weeks after anyone stops qualifying for Working Tax Credit.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-07-13T09:57:34.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388165/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388165/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-07","Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, in what way the eligibility criteria for the pupil premium take account of the level and security of income of parents on (a) zero-hour contracts and (b) temporary contracts.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","5855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388166","Department for Education","false","2015-07-14","<p>Information is not available in the requested format.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2015-07-14T14:28:43.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388166/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388166/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-07","STEM Subjects","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what proportion of students in (a) single-sex and (b) mixed schools who study STEM subjects after GCSE were (i) male and (ii) female in (A) Portsmouth South constituency, (B) the South of England and (C) the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Flick Drummond","Portsmouth South","Mrs Flick Drummond","5980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388167","Department for Education","false","2015-07-15","<p>Local authorities (LAs) have a statutory duty to support and encourage young people to participate, and to secure sufficient suitable education and training for all young people. The Government has published guidance for LAs on implementing these duties effectively, and has made available research into good practice including tips for LAs on implementing raising the participation age. LAs also take part in regional meetings to share good practice, and can access advice and guidance from high performing authorities. The Department for Education publishes LA participation data three times a year and LAs are encouraged to benchmark their performance against other areas and prioritise the improvement of participation levels accordingly.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-15T13:59:05.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388167/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388167/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-07","Education: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Answer of 26 March 2015 to Question 228861, what support and advice her Department offers to local authorities which are having difficulty in getting young people to participate in education.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","5793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388168","Department for Education","false","2015-07-15","<p>At the end of 2014 the proportion of 16 and 17 year olds in England not in education and training fell to 6.4% - its lowest level since consistent records began and 3.0ppt lower than at the end of 2010. This means that more young people have the opportunity to gain the skills and qualifications to reach their potential. Local Authorities (LAs) have a statutory duty to support and encourage young people to participate, and to secure sufficient suitable education and training for all young people - they can access guidance and advice on this from the Government and from one another. Government funded schemes such as the Youth Contract and Youth Engagement Fund pilots are available to support the participation of young people, along with other support from schools and colleges - and via European Social Fund provision and pilots for Jobcentre Plus to support young people to access local employment and training opportunities.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-15T14:01:08.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388168/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388168/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-07","Education: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Answer of 26 March 2015 to Question 228861, what mechanism her Department has in place to master those areas of the country which have higher than average levels of 16 and 17 year olds not in education or training.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","5794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388169","Department for Education","false","2015-07-14","<p>The government has made a series of important reforms to improve permanence for looked after children. We gave them a high profile launch at the British Association of Adoption and Fostering conference on permanence in October 2014, where they formed the centrepiece of my speech.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Care Planning and Fostering (Miscellaneous Amendments) Regulations 2015 and associated guidance came into force on 1 April 2015. We have promoted these reforms to local authorities via the Association of Directors of Children’s Services (ADCS) bulletin in March 2015; and again through the Department for Education’s official communication to local authority Directors of Children’s Services, Chief Executives and Lead Members in June.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-07-14T14:24:20.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388169/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388169/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-07","Care Planning and Fostering Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to raise awareness of the Care Planning and Fostering Regulations 2015 and their accompanying guidance among local authorities.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","5797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388170","Department for Education","false","2015-07-13","<p>The information requested is contained in the following table:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Funding provided to Kids Company by DfE (and predecessor bodies).</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td>2005-2008</td><td>£3.4m (total)</td><td>Invest to Save programme.</td></tr><tr><td>2008-2009</td><td>£4.7m</td><td>Youth Sector Development Fund</td></tr><tr><td>2009-2010</td><td>£4.2m</td><td>Youth Sector Development Fund</td></tr><tr><td>2010-2011</td><td>£4.6m</td><td>Youth Sector Development Fund</td></tr><tr><td>2011-2012</td><td>£4.785m</td><td>VCS transition grants programme</td></tr><tr><td>2012-2013</td><td>£4.785m</td><td>VCS transition grants programme</td></tr><tr><td>2013-2014</td><td>£4.0m</td><td>VCS National Prospectus programme</td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-07-13T16:07:02.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388170/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388170/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-07","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what funds her Department paid to Kids Company in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","5834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388171","Department for Education","false","2015-07-13","<p>Commercially sensitive information and confidential discussions are not published by the Department for Education as to do so could harm the frankness and candour of negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-07-13T15:59:23.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388171/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388171/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-07","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will publish all correspondence between her Department and Camila Batmanghelidjh on Kids Company in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","5832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388172","Women and Equalities","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Government has no plans to extend the Civil Partnership Act 2004 to opposite sex couples.</p><p> </p><p>The Government carried out a review of the operation and future of the Civil Partnership Act 2004 required by The Marriage (Same Sex Couples) Act 2013, which included a full public consultation inviting views on potential changes to civil partnership.</p><p> </p><p>The Government published a report, following the review, which concluded that the Government would not make any changes.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2015-07-14T06:06:17.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388172/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388172/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2015-07-07","Civil Partnerships Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether she has any plans to bring forward an amendment to the Civil Partnerships Act 2004 to permit opposite sex civil partnerships.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","5833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388173","Department for Education","false","2015-07-13","<p>One person has been seconded to Kids Company from the Department for Education since 2011. The secondee was based at the Head Office of Kids Company at Blackfriars Road, London, SE1, for a period of 13 months. The costs of the secondment were met in full by the department.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The terms of reference were set out in the advertisement for the secondment and we have placed a copy of this in the House Library.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2015-07-13T16:00:22.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388173/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388173/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-07","Kids Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the terms of reference were of each secondment of officials from her Department to Kids Company since 2011; where each such official was based; and what departmental resources were involved with each such secondment.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","5835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388174","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-13","<p>In November 2014 DECC published estimates of the impact of energy and climate change policies on energy prices and bills[1]. The report included an estimate of the impact of the package of measures for household energy bills announced at the 2013 Autumn Statement.</p><p>The report set out that the total reduction in individual household energy bills will depend on the energy supplier but estimated that, on average, this package was worth around £50 (including VAT) per household in 2014, broken down as follows:</p><p> </p><p>· A Government Electricity Rebate of £12 on household electricity bills in 2014/15 and 2015/16 delivered by energy suppliers.</p><p> </p><p>· A reduction in the cost of the Energy Company Obligation (ECO). While costs will vary across companies, the major energy suppliers announced that the changes will result in an average £30-£35 off bills in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>· Voluntary action by electricity distribution network operators (DNOs) to reduce network costs in 2014/15, leading to a further one-off deferral of around £5 on electricity bills on average.</p><p><em>[1]</em><em> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/estimated-impacts-of-energy-and-climate-change-policies-on-energy-prices-and-bills-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/estimated-impacts-of-energy-and-climate-change-policies-on-energy-prices-and-bills-2014</a> </em></p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-13T11:44:49.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388174/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388174/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-07","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the average change in household energy bills which occurred as a result of measures announced in the 2013 Autumn Statement.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","5786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388175","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-13","<p>DECC domestic energy bill estimates are only produced at Public Energy Supply (PES) regional level, we do not have bill data for constituency level. The St Helens North constituency covers two PES regions, North West and Merseyside &amp; North Wales.</p><p>The tables below shows the estimated average annual 2014 energy bill (2015 data is not yet available) for customers in the UK, and the two relevant PES region.</p><p>These are based on an assumed annual consumption of 3,800 kWh of electricity and 15,000 kWh of gas per year.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong><em>2014</em></strong></p></td><td><p><em>Electricity</em></p></td><td><p><em>Gas</em></p></td><td><p><em>Total</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>£592</p></td><td><p>£752</p></td><td><p>£1,344</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>£596</p></td><td><p>£748</p></td><td><p>£1,344</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Merseyside and North Wales</p></td><td><p>£634</p></td><td><p>£755</p></td><td><p>£1,389</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p><strong><em>2010</em></strong></p></td><td><p><em>Electricity</em></p></td><td><p><em>Gas</em></p></td><td><p><em>Total</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>£474</p></td><td><p>£564</p></td><td><p>£1,038</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>£451</p></td><td><p>£567</p></td><td><p>£1,018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Merseyside and North Wales</p></td><td><p>£489</p></td><td><p>£567</p></td><td><p>£1,056</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-13T11:47:17.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388175/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388175/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-07","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the average domestic energy bill in (a) St Helens North constituency, (b) the North West and (c) the UK in 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","5953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388176","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Government has implemented a range of measures to support vulnerable households reduce their energy bills, including:</p><p>· Winter Fuel Payment - worth up to £300, estimated £ 2.15 billion spent in 2013/14 (specifically for pensioners);</p><p> </p><p>· Cold Weather Payments - provide £25 for every week of a cold spell – in the last cold winter (2012/13) 5.8 million payments were made, estimated over £140 million spent in 2012/13 (specifically for those on low incomes);</p><p> </p><p>· Warm Home Discount: provides assistance to around 2 million low income and vulnerable households with their energy costs each year. Over 1.4 million of the poorest pensioners received £140 off their electricity bill last winter (14/15), over 1.3 million of them automatically.</p><p> </p><p>· Nearly £3m invested over 3 years in the Big Energy Saving Network to help the most vulnerable get the best deal for them and access to available help.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-13T11:49:40.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388176/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388176/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-07","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what support her Department offers to (a) people on low incomes, (b) people who live in rented accommodation and (c) pensioners to enable them to switch to the lowest priced energy tariffs.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388177","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-13","<p>We will consider the CMA’s provisional findings carefully and respond shortly.</p><p>In the meantime this Government continues to focus on keeping bills down through promoting competition, making switching quicker and easier, and providing direct help to the most vulnerable.</p><p>We have already:</p><p>· tackled barriers hindering the entry and growth of independent suppliers through the Challenger Business Programme</p><p>· halved the time it takes to switch supplier;</p><p>· put QR codes on bills to allow switching through mobile phones</p><p>· delivered a national switching campaign, resulting in £38 million savings by 130,000 households switching energy supplier; and</p><p>· provided nearly £3m over three years to the Big Energy Saving Network which has already helped around 220,000 vulnerable consumers with their energy bills.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-13T11:54:47.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388177/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388177/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-07","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the findings of the report by the Competition and Markets Authority on its provisional finding on its energy market investigation, published on 7 July 2015; and what steps she is taking to ensure that customers are not paying too much for their energy bills.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388178","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-13","<p>Local authorities have a responsibility to consider appropriate remediation measures, which could include signage if appropriate, where there is evidence of a potential risk to health in the environment. Local authorities in England are advised by Public Health England in relation to health risks associated with radioactive contamination and by the Environment Agency in respect of appropriate remediation measures.</p><p>Operators of all nuclear facilities in England must comply with environmental permits issued by the Environment Agency. The Environment Agency also conducts ongoing independent monitoring of the level of radioactivity in the environment and publishes results annually. There is no indication from this programme of a potential health risk in relation to the nuclear facilities at Hinkley Point.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-13T11:43:27.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388178/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388178/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-07","Hinkley Point Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what information she has received from public protection authorities in North Somerset on compliance at Hinckley Point nuclear facilities with the provision of the Health and Social Care Act 2012 requiring the display of public notices warning of areas where pollution is a potential health risk.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388179","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-13","<p>We will consider the CMA’s provisional findings carefully and respond shortly.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-07-13T11:49:12.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388179/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388179/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-07","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the  Competition and Markets Authority's provisional findings on the energy market, published on 6 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","5908"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388180","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>Capercaillies are protected under the Wild Birds Directive and its habitat is afforded protection through the network of Special Protection Areas (SPAs) classified under the Directive. In England the species does not occur in sufficient qualifying numbers to warrant SPA provision.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-07-13T17:04:07.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388180/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388180/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Capercaillie: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to increase numbers of and habitat for capercaillies.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","6054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388181","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Environment Agency funds a targeted campaign called “<em>Building Bridges” </em>which educates migrant anglers about English fishing laws and customs. The project operates at a national level, as well as focussing on specific areas with high numbers of migrant anglers. It is currently delivered by the Angling Trust.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>More details can be found at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.anglingtrust.net/page.asp?section=709&amp;sectionTitle=Building+Bridges+with+Migrant+Anglers" target="_blank">http://www.anglingtrust.net/page.asp?section=709&amp;sectionTitle=Building+Bridges+with+Migrant+Anglers</a></p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T10:35:00.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388181/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388181/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Angling: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will request the Environment Agency to conduct a public information campaign for non-UK passport holders on fish stock management in the UK's waterways and rivers to improve the long-term sustainability of freshwater fish stocks.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","5907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388182","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>In England, we will take forward our manifesto commitment to produce a 25 year strategy for the environment, which will include biodiversity<em>. </em>Our approach will be designed to meet the habitat needs of many species including hedgehogs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Agri-environment schemes are the principle means of improving habitats and the wider environment on farmland in England. The Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package and other measures in the new Countryside Stewardship scheme will help to provide suitable habitat for a range of wildlife in England including hedgehogs.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-07-13T16:57:54.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388182/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388182/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Hedgehogs: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to improve habitats for hedgehogs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388183","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>Defra is investing £4.2million over three years in the Sustainable Intensification research Platform (SIP). This is investigating integrated approaches for farmers to increase their productivity while simultaneously protecting and enhancing the natural environment.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T13:01:31.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388183/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388183/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Food: Crops","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department plans to take to increase the effective use of agricultural land for food production.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388184","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package options within our new Countryside Stewardship scheme will be of benefit to the grey partridge by providing winter feeding, nesting sites and food for chicks through appropriate management of farmland habitats.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-07-13T17:00:33.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388184/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388184/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Partridges: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to improve habitats for grey partridges.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388185","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-14","<p>In England, we will take forward our manifesto commitment to produce a 25 year strategy for the environment, which will include biodiversity<em>. </em>Our approach will be designed to meet the habitat needs of many species including butterflies. In England’s National Pollinator Strategy we are aiming to expand flower rich habitats across different types of land to benefit pollinators including butterflies.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The England network of protected areas provides benefits for many species even when those areas are not specifically designated for the conservation of those particular species. This network includes local and national sites protected under domestic legislation and international sites protected under European and International law. Some of these sites are specifically designated for species of particular importance, including the marsh fritillary butterfly, which is a notified feature of a number of Special Areas of Conservation, designated under the Habitats Directive</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Agri-environment schemes play a major role in the conservation of butterflies in England. For instance, across grassland habitats in Dorset, between 1990 and 2010 the marsh fritillary increased in abundance by around 278% on land managed under these schemes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the summer of 2014 the critically endangered high brown fritillary experienced its best season since 2004 with numbers increasing by more than 180% as compared to 2013 across Dartmoor, Exmoor, and Morecambe Bay in Lancashire and sites in the Lake District.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package in the new Countryside Stewardship scheme contain options to improve habitats and provide nectar sources for butterflies. It will play a key role in supporting the National Pollinator Strategy.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-07-14T14:06:53.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388185/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388185/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Butterflies: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to improve habitats for butterflies.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388186","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>In 2014-15, 6.3% of rod licence income was used to fund Environment Agency officers carrying out compliance checks and enforcing regulations.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T10:31:39.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388186/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388186/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Angling: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of the cost of fishing licences is allocated to the protection of fish stocks through the deployment of bailiffs.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","5906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388187","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-10","<p>The development of new traps is a matter for industry. However, all spring trap designs have to be approved by Defra under Spring Trap Approval Orders before they can be used and the approvals process assesses the humaneness of the trap.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-07-10T16:12:35.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388187/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388187/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Trapping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what work her Department has undertaken on development of a humane trap for small pest control in rural areas.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388188","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-10","<p>Defra does not hold this information. However, partly in response to intelligence reports of poaching received by the National Wildlife Crime Unit through police forces, poaching is one of the UK wildlife crime priorities. If Defra received reports of poaching, either the information would be passed to the police, or the person reporting the activity would be advised to contact the police.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-07-10T16:14:29.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388188/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388188/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Poaching","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many incidents of poaching of animals there have been in the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388189","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>Defra does not hold such information, nor has it made any recent estimates.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Published sources estimate that there are over one and a half million wild deer in the UK, of which 350,000 are culled each year by over 100,000 deer stalkers. The industry claims that around 2,500 jobs are provided by deer management. There are a further 32,000 deer on farms in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","5896","2015-07-13T16:55:31.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388189/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388189/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Deer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent estimate she has made of the number of deer in the UK; and how many deer are culled each year.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388190","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>Our annual accounts show that the price of venison rose from £3.55 per kilogram in 2009 to £4.94 per kilogram in 2014.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T12:08:19.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388190/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388190/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Venison: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information her Department holds on changes in the price of venison in the UK in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388191","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>Defra does not hold such information, nor has it made any recent estimates.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Published sources estimate that there are over one and a half million wild deer in the UK, of which 350,000 are culled each year by over 100,000 deer stalkers. The industry claims that around 2,500 jobs are provided by deer management. There are a further 32,000 deer on farms in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","5894","2015-07-13T16:55:31.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388191/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388191/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Deer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people are employed in jobs relating to deer farming and hunting; and if she will estimate how many people participate in deer shooting.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388192","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given on 9 July 2015, PQ UIN 5754.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T10:29:34.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388192/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388192/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Oilseed Rape","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions she has had on the potential health effects of the cultivation of oilseed rape with the (a) Secretary of State for Health, (b) Secretary of State for Scotland and (c) Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Mike Weir","Angus","Mike Weir","5870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388193","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>The rod licensing regime is currently being reviewed by the Environment Agency. This is evaluating the scope for a broader range of licensing options, including the ways of issuing licences and the greater future use of digital channels.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T10:37:18.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388193/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388193/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Angling: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will amend the fishing licensing regime to enable day licences to be more easily issued by independent fishing venues without requiring costly security measures.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","5917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388194","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Airports Commission undertook a considerable amount of work to assess the air quality implications of the three shortlisted expansion schemes. The impact on local air quality and how this affects compliance with EU air quality standards is something the Government will be considering carefully when deciding on additional runway capacity.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-13T10:56:23.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388194/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388194/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-07","Air Pollution: Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the findings on page 27 of the Airports Commission: final report, published 1 July 2015, what assessment he has made of the effect on compliance (a) with EU air quality limits and (b) of air quality receptors with 2030 air quality limits of a decision to build a third runway at Heathrow.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","6029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388195","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-13","<p /> <p>The Radcliffe Bay Petroleum Storage Depot is subject to the Control of Major Accident Hazard (COMAH) Regulations 2015 at Upper Tier. This requires it to produce a Safety Report that includes an assessment of the hazards posed by the site to its environmental surroundings including the Severn Estuary, the measures in place to prevent an accident and a plan for mitigatory action, including clean-up, in the event of an accident. Through these Regulations the Environment Agency is working with the site to ensure that adequate and appropriate risk assessments are in place.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-07-13T14:09:58.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388195/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388195/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-07","Severn Estuary: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the likelihood of a major contamination of the Severn Estuary downhill of the Radcliffe Bay Petroleum Storage Depot in North Somerset.","false","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox","5875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388196","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>The oilseed rape harvest in 2014 saw an increase in UK production of 16% to nearly 2.5 million tonnes following favourable weather conditions during the 2013/14 growing season. This higher production reflects an increase in yield of oilseed rape by 23%. The area sown to oilseed rape in 2014 was 675 thousand hectares, which was nearly 6% lower than that sown in 2013. Full details can be found in the Farming Statistics release which was published on 18 December 2014 on the Defra website.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A recent survey carried out by the Agriculture and Horticulture Development Board (AHDB) Cereals and Oilseeds team indicates that the area sown to oilseed rape in Great Britain in 2015 has fallen to 627 thousand hectares. Provisional production estimates for the 2015 harvest will be published by Defra in October.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T10:40:36.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388196/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388196/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Oilseed Rape","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the amount of oilseed rape produced since December 2013.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","5948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388197","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>Recording from volunteer societies provides a rich source of data and complex modelling can be used to produce trends. In 2014, using this approach, Defra published a pilot indicator of changes in the bee population in the UK between 1980 and 2010. Between 1980 and 2010, the indicator fell to 62 percent of its 1980 value. It is not yet possible to provide a trend since 2013; further development of the indicator should allow for assessment in future years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government continues to work to strengthen monitoring of insect pollinators. In early 2014, Defra commissioned a two-year research study to design and test a robust and affordable national monitoring framework that can be applied across the UK. This study is due to be completed later this year. It has made significant progress with engaging key audiences involved in insect and wider biodiversity monitoring and is currently testing pilot methods at sites across the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","5559","2015-07-13T10:22:23.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388197/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388197/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Bees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the change in the UK's bee population since December 2013.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","5949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388198","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>The most common type of LA-MRSA in Europe belongs to clonal complex 398 (CC398). MRSA CC398 is less virulent and transmissible compared to other strains and is unlikely to pass from person to person and become endemic in the human population.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However studies from various countries in continental Europe have demonstrated that in limited circumstances it is possible for MRSA CC398 to be transmitted from animals to people. This tends to be constrained to those who have regular contact with livestock that are carrying the bacteria, in particular pigs.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T16:53:58.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388198/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388198/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Livestock: MRSA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Oral Answer of the Minister of State, the hon. Member for Camborne and Redruth of 18 June 2015, Official Report, column 445, what the evidential basis is for the statement that livestock-associated MRSA does not cross to the human population; and what assessment her Department has made of evidence that MRSA ST398 can and does pass from pigs to humans, causing serious infections and fatalities.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","5999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388199","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-15","<p>Defra works closely with representatives from across the food sector industries and Devolved Administrations on supply chain resilience issues. We have been in regular contact with regard to the ongoing situation in Calais to ensure that concerns are reflected in response planning.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","5769","2015-07-15T16:25:19.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388199/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388199/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Seafood: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of recent disruption at Calais and closures of the Channel Tunnel on seafood exports.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","5768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388200","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-15","<p>Defra works closely with representatives from across the food sector industries and Devolved Administrations on supply chain resilience issues. We have been in regular contact with regard to the ongoing situation in Calais to ensure that concerns are reflected in response planning.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","5768","2015-07-15T16:25:19.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388200/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388200/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Seafood: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to support seafood exporters with costs incurred as a result of recent disruption at Calais.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","5769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388201","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Government is currently developing the framework that will guide the development of the 25 year environment plan. This is being led by Defra and will have ongoing input from other Government Departments. There will also be engagement with those with an interest in the health of the natural environment.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","5982","2015-07-14T16:54:34.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388201/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388201/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Biodiversity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what consultations she plans to undertake with (a) other departments and (b) other bodies and people on the development of a 25-year plan to restore the UK's biodiversity.","false","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","5978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388202","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Government is currently developing the framework that will guide the development of the 25 year environment plan. This is being led by Defra and will have ongoing input from other Government Departments. There will also be engagement with those with an interest in the health of the natural environment.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","5978","2015-07-14T16:54:34.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388202/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388202/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Biodiversity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what process the Government plans to establish to develop a 25-year plan to restore the UK's biodiversity; and when she expects to publish that plan.","false","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","5982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388203","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-14","<p>The UK Government raises its opposition to Japan’s whaling under special permit for ‘scientific purposes’ at every appropriate opportunity.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Most recently, the UK Commissioner to the International Whaling Commission (IWC) reiterated the Government’s concerns in relation to Japan’s proposal to resume whaling in the Antarctic at a meeting with the Japanese Commissioner to the IWC in May 2015, and officials from the Japanese Embassy in March 2015. Her Majesty’s Ambassador to Japan and I, as the then Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Farming, Food and Marine Environment, have also both written to the Japanese Government on this issue.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Also quite recently, at the meeting of the Scientific Committee, which advises the IWC, members of the UK’s scientific delegation were proactively involved in discussions surrounding the validity of Japan’s proposed Antarctic Whaling Programme.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-14T13:48:00.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388203/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388203/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Whales: Japan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking in addition to its work at the International Whaling Commission to discourage Japan from resuming Antarctic whaling.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","5946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388204","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Government recognises that longer tenancies for some farm businesses are important to provide tenants with security to invest and grow their businesses. Flexibility to agree contracts that suit a range of business needs is also important to enable a diverse farming sector. We are working closely with industry to develop policy priorities for a 25-year Food and Farming Plan. Agricultural tenancies and other farming business models will be considered as part of these discussions to help deliver a competitive farming sector in future.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","5930","2015-07-13T13:04:59.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388204/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388204/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Farms: Tenants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she plans to include provisions to extend the length of farm business tenancies in her proposed long-term plan for food and farming.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","5928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388205","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Secretary of State has had no discussions with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on this issue.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T13:13:12.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388205/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388205/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Farms: Tenants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on reforming the taxation of let agricultural land to encourage longer-term farm business tenancies.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","5929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388206","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Government recognises that longer tenancies for some farm businesses are important to provide tenants with security to invest and grow their businesses. Flexibility to agree contracts that suit a range of business needs is also important to enable a diverse farming sector. We are working closely with industry to develop policy priorities for a 25-year Food and Farming Plan. Agricultural tenancies and other farming business models will be considered as part of these discussions to help deliver a competitive farming sector in future.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","5928","2015-07-13T13:05:00.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388206/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388206/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Farms: Tenants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to encourage the letting of longer-term farm business tenancies.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","5930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388207","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-13","<p>An assessment of the Agricultural Tenancies Act 1995 was published in 2002. This included the extent to which the Act had improved the economic efficiency of land use. The assessment concluded there was some evidence of an improvement in economic efficiency, but clearer evidence that the Act had resulted in an increase in let land and that Farm Business Tenancies had provided a simple vehicle to enable farm businesses to expand.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Data on the areas of land under different agricultural tenures can be found on GOV.UK (at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/structure-of-the-agricultural-industry-in-england-and-the-uk-at-june" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/structure-of-the-agricultural-industry-in-england-and-the-uk-at-june</a></p><p> </p><p>and <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/farm-rents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/farm-rents</a>).</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-07-13T13:16:42.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388207/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388207/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-07","Farms: Tenants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of the Agricultural Tenancies Act 1995 in improving the efficiency of land use in the agricultural sector.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","5931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388208","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>The unlawful incursion by a Spanish State research vessel into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters on 3 July - during which its probe struck a Royal Navy vessel - was unacceptable. We protested immediately to the Spanish government at a senior level. It is fortunate that no-one was hurt and no serious damage was done.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-07-15T16:38:13.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388208/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388208/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Gibraltar: Spain","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Spanish Government on the most recent incursion into Gibraltar waters by a Spanish vessel.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","5977"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388209","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>On 3 July, our officials were informed by the non-government organisation, Peace Brigades International, about the recent threats encountered by these four Human Rights Defenders (HRDs). Although the Government is unable to interfere in the judicial process of another country, we will continue to monitor specific cases where our resources allow. Our Embassy in Bogotá was already aware of the cases of Claudia Julieta Duque and Jorge Molano. Jorge Molano met our officials in the United Kingdom on 4 June to discuss the security situation of HRDs and justice for victims of the conflict. We remain concerned by the number of threats made against HRDs in Colombia. We regularly raise these concerns with the Colombian government and our Ambassador in Bogotá has discussed human rights issues with the Presidential Adviser for Human Rights and the Attorney-General’s Office.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","5936","2015-07-14T13:23:00.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388209/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388209/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Colombia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will raise threats made against Berenice Celeita, Claudia Julieta Duque, Andrea Torres and Jorge Molano with the Colombian government.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","5935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388210","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>On 3 July, our officials were informed by the non-government organisation, Peace Brigades International, about the recent threats encountered by these four Human Rights Defenders (HRDs). Although the Government is unable to interfere in the judicial process of another country, we will continue to monitor specific cases where our resources allow. Our Embassy in Bogotá was already aware of the cases of Claudia Julieta Duque and Jorge Molano. Jorge Molano met our officials in the United Kingdom on 4 June to discuss the security situation of HRDs and justice for victims of the conflict. We remain concerned by the number of threats made against HRDs in Colombia. We regularly raise these concerns with the Colombian government and our Ambassador in Bogotá has discussed human rights issues with the Presidential Adviser for Human Rights and the Attorney-General’s Office.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","5935","2015-07-14T13:23:00.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388210/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388210/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Colombia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations his Department has received on threats against Colombian human rights defenders Berenice Celeita, Claudia Julieta Duque, Andrea Torres and Jorge Molano.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","5936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388211","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The UK and Pakistan have a shared interest in the battle against terrorism. We are committed to working together in a number of areas to combat the terrorist threat and the extremism that sustains it. UK assistance includes the appointment of the Prime Minister's Counter Terrorism (CT) Capability Envoy, who visits Pakistan regularly and has detailed discussions with the Pakistan Government on a range of CT issues, including Pakistan’s implementation of the National Action Plan against terrorism.</p><p>Both my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for the Home Department (Theresa May) and the National Security Adviser have had discussions with the Pakistan Minister of the Interior and the Chief of Army Staff during their recent visits to the UK.</p><p>The UK-Pakistan Joint Working Group on CT is our framework for continuing dialogue. UK officials at the High Commission in Islamabad and from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and Home Office Counter Terrorism Departments hold regular meetings with their counterparts in the Government of Pakistan to monitor progress and review areas of co-operation. UK assistance includes a long-term commitment to developing rule of law capacity in line with international law and human rights. Alongside this we have pledged further assistance, including UK strategic expertise, capacity development to improve detection and disruption of improvised explosive devices, support to developing effective approaches to countering violent extremism and strengthening aviation and infrastructure security.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-13T14:46:50.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388211/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388211/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Pakistan: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions his officials have had with the Pakistan government on tackling terrorism in that region.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","6044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388212","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","The UK government is concerned by the decision to uphold Nabeel Rajab’s conviction. I raised this case at Ministerial level during my visit to Bahrain in June. We will continue to make clear to the Government of Bahrain that the legitimate exercise of freedom of expression must be respected.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-13T14:58:13.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388212/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388212/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Nabeel Rajab","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Bahrain government on the imprisonment of Nabeel Rajab.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388213","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The UK is providing a wide range of technical assistance to the Government of Bahrain to support its reform programme. FCO officials evaluate training programmes on a regular basis to ensure that projects are on track for delivery and to assess their impact. Bahrain has made progress in its reforms, but more needs to be done to implement fully the recommendations of the Bahrain Independent Commission of Inquiry and UN Universal Period Review. The UK remains committed to supporting Bahrain in this process.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-13T15:02:41.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388213/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388213/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Bahrain: Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will review the assistance that his Department provides to Bahrain for prison reform.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388214","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Government has made clear its opposition to Antarctic whaling. <br><br>Most recently, the UK Commissioner to the International Whaling Commission (IWC) reiterated the Government’s concerns in relation to Japan’s proposal to resume whaling in the Antarctic at a meeting with the Japanese Commissioner to the IWC in May 2015, and with officials from the Japanese Embassy in March 2015. The then Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Natural Environment, Water and Rural Affairs, my hon Friend the Member for Camborne, Redruth and Hayle (Mr George Eustice) and Her Majesty’s Ambassador to Japan, have also both written previously to the Japanese government on this issue.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-07-13T14:11:01.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388214/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388214/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Japan: Whales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to discourage Japan from resuming Antarctic whaling.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","6017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388215","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>During the African Union Summit, I discussed the importance of a lasting peace settlement in South Sudan with Foreign Ministers from a number of regional countries, including Ethiopia and Uganda along with senior officials at the African Union. Most recently, I discussed the urgent need for progress in peace talks with the Kenyan Cabinet Secretary for Foreign Affairs and International Trade, Amina Mohamed, on 8 July 2015.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2015-07-14T13:22:43.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388215/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388215/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","South Sudan: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his international counterparts on the conflict in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388216","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>As the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), said in his speech on 21 May 2015, the Government is concerned that under the current free movement rules, national welfare systems can provide an unintended additional incentive for large migratory movements. Consequently reforming welfare and particularly access to benefits for mobile EU nationals in order to reduce incentives for migration is one of our priorities for the renegotiation. The Prime Minister is working with his European partners to achieve this.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-07-13T14:45:52.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388216/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388216/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","EU Nationals: Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what contingency plan he has made for if it is viable to secure agreement with his EU counterparts for the introduction of a four-year qualifying period for EU nationals to access in-work benefits in negotiating the UK's membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","5881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388217","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>I asked our officials to raise this question with the US Embassy and they were informed of global delays to the US visa system in June which impacted visa processing worldwide. I understand that this has now been resolved.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-07-13T14:05:21.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388217/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388217/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","USA: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he last discussed delays in the processing of visas for UK citizens with the US Ambassador to the UK.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","5812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388218","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>Information on the number of UK citizens waiting for a decision on a US visa application is held by the US authorities and I am therefore unable to make an estimate. We were aware of the delays in processing visa applications in June, but understand this has now been resolved.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-07-13T14:06:34.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388218/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388218/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","USA: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate he has made of the number of UK citizens waiting for a decision on a visa application from the US administration.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","5813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388219","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>We are concerned about the recent rise in the number of small Salafi groups in Gaza that sympathise or self-identify with ISIL. This highlights the urgent need for all the parties to reach an agreement that addresses the underlying causes of conflict in Gaza to restore security under the Palestinian Authority, and reduce the risk of radicalisation inside Gaza. We are monitoring the situation closely.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-14T13:03:09.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388219/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388219/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Gaza: Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received of ISIL-linked terrorists operating in Gaza.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","5798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388220","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>There is no mandatory requirement for staff employed by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office to have fluency in a language. We do not hold the information requested broken down by year, but the latest information on our personnel database shows 37 staff with skills in Urdu, 25 in Punjabi and 1 in Pashto at varying levels, and none in Sindhi. Staff appointed to jobs where proficiency in the local language is essential for their role are offered fulltime language training and many of our locally engaged staff in our Posts overseas are native speakers or are fluent in the local language.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-15T15:32:12.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388220/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388220/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Languages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many fluent (a) Urdu, (b) Punjabi, (c) Pashto and (d) Sindhi speakers his Department employed in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","5827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388221","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>There is no mandatory requirement for staff employed by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office to have fluency in a language. We do not hold the information requested broken down by year, but the latest information on our personnel database shows that we have no staff with registered skills in Hausa, Fulani or Kanuri. Staff appointed to jobs where proficiency in the local language is essential for their role are offered fulltime language training and many of our locally engaged staff in our Posts overseas are native speakers or are fluent in the local language.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-15T15:33:14.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388221/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388221/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Languages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many fluent (a) Hausa, (b) Fulani and (c) Kanuri speakers his Department employed in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","5828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388222","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>There is no mandatory requirement for staff employed by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office to have fluency in a language. We do not hold the information requested broken down by year, but the latest information on our personnel database shows that we have 131 staff with registered skills in Arabic at varying levels. Staff appointed to jobs where proficiency in the local language is essential for their role are offered fulltime language training and many of our locally engaged staff in our Posts overseas are native speakers or are fluent in the local language.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-15T15:33:50.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388222/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388222/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Arabic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many fluent Arabic speakers his Department employed in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","5829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388223","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The long standing position of the UK is that it is for India and Pakistan to find a lasting resolution to the situation in Kashmir, taking into account the wishes of the Kashmiri people. It is not for the UK to prescribe a solution or to act as a mediator. We follow developments in the region closely and we encourage both India and Pakistan to maintain positive dialogue, but the pace and scope of this is for them to determine. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), discussed the situation in Kashmir when he met with the Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in November 2014 and when he met with the Indian Minister for External Affairs, Sushma Swaraj in March 2015.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-07-13T14:20:56.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388223/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388223/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Kashmir","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the UN and the governments of Pakistan, India and China on steps towards a peaceful resolution to the territorial dispute in Kashmir.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","5821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388224","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>We receive regular media reports of continued heavy fighting in Kachin State. This includes reports of an escalation of violence in June, involving clashes in the vicinity of Hpakant. It is difficult to independently verify these reports owing to a lack of access to conflict affected areas, but a DFID team visited from 8-11 June to assess the effect of conflict on the civilian population, including on the over 100,000 displaced people currently living in camps. <br><br>We remain very concerned that the continued conflict sustains an environment where human rights violations, including the sexual abuse of women caught up in the conflict, can and do occur, as was starkly demonstrated by the terrible case of the two teachers raped and killed in January this year in neighbouring Shan State. We have made clear to the government of Burma that any allegations of human rights abuses must be dealt with through a clear, independent and transparent investigative and prosecutorial process that meets international standards.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-07-13T15:42:51.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388224/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388224/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Burma: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports the Government has received on human rights violations by the Burmese Army in Kachin state, Burma; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","6046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388225","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>I have not met the Burmese Rohingya community in the UK since the Bay of Bengal and Andaman Sea humanitarian crisis emerged in May. However, our officials met a senior Burmese Muslim representative in London in June to discuss the crisis, and I called in the Burmese Ambassador to raise my concerns. Previously I have met many Burmese groups, including community and religious leaders from within the Rohingya community, both in the UK and during my visits to Burma.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-07-13T14:13:52.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388225/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388225/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Rohingya: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what meetings he has held with the ethnic Rohingya community in the UK regarding the Rhoingya refugee crisis.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","6047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388226","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>We welcome the release of thousands of political prisoners under the current Burmese government. However, we remain concerned by the continued arrests, detentions and sentencing of political activists, with an estimated minimum of 150 remaining behind bars at the end of May 2015, and a further 450 awaiting trial following arrests throughout 2014 and early 2015. <br><br>Officials from our Embassy in Rangoon meet regularly with civil society on this issue, and we continue to raise our concerns with the government of Burma at the highest levels. Most recently, the then Minister of State at the Home Office, Lynne Featherstone, raised this issue directly with Minister for the President’s Office, U Soe Thein, during her visit to Burma in January. We continue to lobby on individual cases. We also raise our concerns publicly in our Annual Report on Human Rights and in multilateral fora such as the UN General Assembly and the Human Rights Council, where the UK co-sponsored a Resolution in March that called for the unconditional release of all political prisoners.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-07-13T14:16:54.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388226/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388226/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Burma: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to secure the release of all political prisoners in Burma.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","6048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388227","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>We remain deeply concerned by the persecution of religious and other minorities in Pakistan. The Pakistan Government can be under no doubt as to the importance we place on addressing these issues. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), discussed our concerns at the misuse of the blasphemy laws in Pakistan with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in November 2014, as did the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) in December. In June I stressed our ongoing concern about minorities in Pakistan with the Pakistan High Commissioner to London.</p><p>We will continue to urge the Government of Pakistan to protect the human rights of all its citizens and our concerns about minorities in Pakistan are documented in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office annual Human Rights Report.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-14T13:10:37.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388227/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388227/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Pakistan: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with government officials in Pakistan on the persecution of religious and social minorities in that country.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","5947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388228","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>We have no plans to seek the advice of the Venice Commission. We will of course consider their recommendations very carefully when framing amendments to the European Union Referendum Bill, including the 2007 &quot;Code of Good Practice on Referendums&quot;.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-07-13T15:47:09.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388228/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388228/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will seek the advice of the Venice Commission on the circumstances in which it would be appropriate for the resources available to (a) the Prime Minister and (b) other elements of the Government to be utilised during the purdah period in the forthcoming EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","6004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388229","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","£2.1 million has been allocated for assistance to Bahrain in 2015-16 to support the government of Bahrain in its reform programme, aimed at strengthening human rights and the rule of law.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-13T14:57:03.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388229/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388229/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Bahrain","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department has allocated for assistance to Bahrain in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388230","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>We, together with EU and international partners, have consistently set out our concerns about breaches of fundamental rights, freedom of speech and the politicisation of institutions to Prime Minister Gruevski and other representatives of the Macedonian government. The British Embassy in Skopje demarched, along with members of the Quint (US, EU delegation, France, Germany and Italy) Prime Minister Gruevski in March and again in May in view of the ongoing political crisis in Macedonia. I discussed the situation in Macedonia with Foreign Minister Poposki in Brussels on 19 May.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-07-15T15:25:45.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388230/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388230/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Macedonia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the government of Macedonia on (a) mass surveillance, (b) individual independence and (c) freedom of speech.","false","Biography information for Mr Pat McFadden","Wolverhampton South East","Mr Pat McFadden","5920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388231","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>My Department, including the British Embassy in Skopje, is in close and regular contact with civil society and political representatives on freedom of speech and surveillance in Macedonia.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-07-15T15:25:07.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388231/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388231/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Macedonia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has received on freedom of speech and surveillance in Macedonia.","false","Biography information for Mr Pat McFadden","Wolverhampton South East","Mr Pat McFadden","5919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388232","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>Bahrain has had a de facto moratorium in place on the use of the death penalty since 2010, although we are concerned a number of individuals have received the death penalty sentence since then.</p><p>The UK opposes the death penalty around the world because we believe it undermines human dignity, there is no evidence that it works as a deterrent and any error made in its application is irreversible.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-13T15:06:54.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388232/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388232/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","Bahrain: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to take steps to encourage the introduction of a moratorium on the use of the death penalty in Bahrain; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388233","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>The United Kingdom takes all human rights issues seriously and looks to tackle slave labour and human trafficking in coordination with our international partners.</p><p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) met Malaysian Foreign Minister Anifah in June. He welcomed Malaysia’s regional leadership on the recent migration crisis and encouraged a continued regional approach. Our officials have lobbied ASEAN member states, Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia, to do the same. We have cooperated with Malaysia on human trafficking, including at a workshop in January and an earlier visit by Malaysian officials to the UK Human Trafficking Centre. In June, senior officials met the head of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees in Kuala Lumpur.</p><p>Since the Thai coup of May 2014, high-level political bilateral exchanges with the Thai military government have been postponed or cancelled. However, as part of our inaugural strategic dialogue with Thailand in 2013, which I co-chaired, the UK and Thailand committed to work together to combat transnational crimes, including human trafficking. We continue to look for opportunities to raise this issue where and when we can, including in future negotiations over an EU-Thailand Free Trade Agreement, where issues of regulation and labour standards will feature prominently.</p><p>We continue to work with the Thai authorities on the disruption of human trafficking and irregular migration and have issued statements in support of activists working on the issue of migrants’ human rights. We also work with UK industry to support ethical supply chains and promote greater awareness within the UK of where products and services have been sourced.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-07-15T13:37:04.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388233/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388233/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","South East Asia: Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in Malaysia and Thailand on ensuring that people are not trafficked from those countries.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388234","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>The question in the Bill is simple, short and fair. We have no plans to include a separate question.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-07-15T15:28:08.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388234/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388234/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if the Government will include in its proposed referendum on UK membership of the EU a separate question on approving any changes that have been agreed to the UK's terms of membership of the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388235","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>My Department has not received any such recent reports.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-14T13:06:15.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388235/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388235/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388235/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","USA: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent reports he has received on potentially unsafe transit of nuclear warheads by the US military.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388236","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Foreign Secretary has made no such representations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-14T13:08:06.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388236/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388236/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388236/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","USA: Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the US government on the safety of that country's nuclear missiles.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388237","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The support that the Foreign and Commonwealth Office can offer British Nationals who are victims of crime abroad is described in our publication, Support for British Nationals Abroad: A Guide. This can be found on http://tinyurl.com/pr3buzf.</p><p>In summary, the assistance that the Foreign and Commonwealth Office is appropriate to the individual circumstances of each case. It may include for example:</p><p>- Issuing replacement emergency travel documents. <br>- Providing information about transferring funds. <br>- Providing details of local lawyers and other services for victims of crime. <br>- Contacting family or friends to assist with funds.</p><p>We also provide travel advice for British Nationals. This is tailored to the situation in the country being visited. For example, in our travel advice for Greece we have advised British Nationals to make sure they take sufficient euros in cash to cover the duration of their stay as well as taking appropriate security precautions against theft.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2015-07-13T14:10:28.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388237/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388237/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388237/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-07","British Nationals Abroad: Theft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what advice his Department provides to British nationals who have cash stolen while on holiday abroad.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","5904"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388238","Department of Health","false","2015-07-13","<p>We do not hold this information centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Revised statutory guidance on autism for local authorities and the National Health Service was issued on 26 March this year and continued to include the importance of having access locally to a diagnostic pathway and improving the quality of services for adults with autism.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) provides national guidance and advice to improve health and social care. NICE has published three clinical guidelines on autism and a quality standard. It has also produced an implementation pack on developing multi-agency local autism teams and support for commissioning autism services, which outlines key actions that commissioners should take. Although arrangements for referrals for autism diagnosis are a matter for local determination, NHS England has a role in assuring the process is adopted. Representations on clinical approaches concerning autism are normally forwarded by the Department to NHS organisations or other relevant authorities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Public Health England oversees an annual autism self-assessment exercise amongst local authority areas and their partners. In 2013/14, it reported that 4,677 people had received a diagnosis of an autistic spectrum condition in the year to the end of March 2014, based on data submitted from 102 of a possible 152 local authority areas. In the same exercise, the average waiting time between referral and assessment as reported by 110 local authority areas was 29.6 weeks. This was the first time these questions had been asked in this form. The results of the 2014/15 exercise will be published in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","5990 ; 5991 ; 5993 ; 5994","2015-07-13T14:57:20.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388238/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388238/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388238/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-07","Autism: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received from (a) specialist bodies and (b) charities on treatment options for autism spectrum disorder on the NHS; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","5992"
