"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388368","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-15","<p /> <p>Official statistics for Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) processing times are not readily available and to provide the information requested would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-07-15T11:32:05.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388368/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388368/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388368/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-07","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average waiting time for an Employment and Support Allowance assessment has been in (a) St Helens North constituency, (b) the North West and (c) the UK since the instigation of those assessments.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","5981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388369","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-13","<p /> <p>The ability to derive a basic state pension or increase of basic state pension based on the National Insurance contributions of a spouse or civil partner is a feature of the current state pension scheme. It will continue to be available to people who reach state pension age before the introduction of the new state pension on 6 April 2016 and who will, therefore, remain in the current scheme.</p><p> </p><p>This provision, which dates from the 1940s, is rapidly becoming redundant as the majority of individuals who have spent most of their working lives in the UK have the opportunity to build up a state pension in their own right, either through working or credits that recognise a wide range of circumstances, including caring responsibilities. The new state pension is designed to reflect the working lives of people reaching state pension age now and in the future. It will accordingly be based on an individual’s own National Insurance contributions.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-07-13T16:30:09.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388369/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388369/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388369/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-07","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to reverse the decision to remove derived entitlements to the basic state pension; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","6018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388370","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-15","<p>National Insurance credits are generally available to people who are unable to work and pay contributions for example if they are unemployed, incapable of work or caring for others.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>National Insurance credits are awarded automatically with qualifying social security benefits; otherwise applications are required to determine eligibility.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is introducing a new credit for those who reach State Pension age on or after 6 April 2016. It will be available to the spouses and civil partners of members of HM Forces for past periods spent accompanying their Service partner on postings outside the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Those not eligible for National Insurance credits may be able to fill gaps in their record to protect certain benefits by paying voluntary contributions. These are subject to time limits; and higher rate provisions when paid late.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For those who would like further information on their National Insurance record they should go to the GOV.UK website <a href="https://www.gov.uk/voluntary-national-insurance-contributions" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/voluntary-national-insurance-contributions</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-07-15T11:56:27.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388370/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388370/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388370/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-07","National Insurance Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what arrangements exist to support those who have fallen behind with national insurance contributions in fully accessing contributory benefits.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","5861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388371","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-15","<p /> <p>People with hearing difficulties can benefit from the same support to find work as other disabled people through provision such as the Work Programme and Work Choice.</p><p> </p><p>In addition we are launching a new programme, Specialist Employability Support (SES), in September. It focuses on helping those for whom other provision such as Work Choice or Work Programme is not suitable and one of the programme providers will support people with hearing difficulties in preparing for work.</p><p> </p><p>SES replaces the Residential Training contracts and is expected to double the number of people supported at the same cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-07-15T11:37:57.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388371/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388371/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388371/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-07","Employment Schemes: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department provides to people with hearing difficulties in finding work.","false","Biography information for Ben Howlett","Bath","Ben Howlett","5858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388372","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-15","<p /> <p>The Department conducts an Equality Analysis before introducing changes, all proposals are assessed in line with the current public sector equality duties. It will show the Department has demonstrated that due regard has been paid when developing these services on the grounds of protected characteristics. This includes disabled people.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-07-15T16:07:10.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388372/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388372/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388372/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-07","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effects of conditionality on employment and support allowance claimants with mental health problems.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","5860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388373","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-13","<p /> <p>The Department intends to publish figures on the number of hardship applications and awards over the summer and I have asked my officials to set a publication date. This will allow more recent figures to be included than those that could be included in May. The publication will include figures covering the whole of Great Britain.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-07-13T14:01:41.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388373/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388373/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388373/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-07","Social Security Benefits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2015 to Question 225002, when his Department plans to publish statistics on the number of hardship applications and awards in Scotland; and for what reason those statistics were not published in May 2015.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","5868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388555","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-13","<p>The RAF Charitable Trust are doing further detailed work, following on from the March 2015 review. Their report will be submitted to the RAF for consideration shortly.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-07-13T16:25:45.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388555/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388555/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Air Displays","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress has been made by RAF Charitable Enterprises on its review of RAF air shows.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","900929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388833","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave earlier today to the hon. Members for Redditch (Karen Lumley) and Southend West (David Amess).</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-07-13T16:32:10.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388833/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388833/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388833/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-07","Islamic State","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to defeat ISIL.","false","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","900920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390040","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>I have had discussions with the Leader of the House on this matter and look forward to this afternoon’s debate.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-15T14:08:45.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390040/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390040/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-07-07","English Votes for English Laws","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with the Leader of the House on the effect of the Government's proposed changes to voting procedures in the House on the representation of constituencies in Scotland; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Yvonne Fovargue","Makerfield","Yvonne Fovargue","900945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390041","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>The UK and Scottish Governments continue to work closely with one another on the implementation of the Scottish Rate of Income Tax. The question now is how the Scottish Government will use the new power, when it comes into effect in April 2016.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-15T14:12:44.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390041/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390041/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-07-07","Income Tax: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent discussions he has had with Ministers of the Scottish Government on progress on implementing the Scottish rate of income tax.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","900942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390042","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>We believe the United Kingdom’s interests will best be served by membership of a reformed European Union. That is why we will negotiate a new settlement for Britain in Europe, and then ask the British people to decide the question in a referendum.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2015-07-15T14:10:12.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390042/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390042/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-07-07","UK Membership of EU: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what assessment he has made of the value to Scotland of the UK remaining in the EU.","false","Biography information for Neil Carmichael","Stroud","Neil Carmichael","900943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387694","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>We are aware of the request made by two members of the Russian Parliament that this matter be examined, and understand that the Russian Prosecutor-General's office is obliged to do so. We do not assess that there will be any practical consequences of this process; the independence of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania is clearly established. The UK never recognised the annexation of the Baltic States by the Soviet Union.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-15T12:31:21.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387694/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387694/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","Russia: Baltic States","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the decision of the Russian Prosecutor General's office, following a request by members of the Russian Parliament, to examine whether the Soviet Union acted legally when it recognised the Baltic states' independence in 1991.","false","Biography information for Lord Balfe",,"Lord Balfe","HL1071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387695","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Government has made no estimate of when this will happen.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-20T10:49:07.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387695/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387695/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387695/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Television: Internet","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of when television will be delivered predominantly across the internet.","false","Biography information for Lord Inglewood",,"Lord Inglewood","HL1072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387696","Home Office","false","2015-07-20","<p>On Thursday 12 March 2015, the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse was set up with statutory powers under the 2005 Inquiries Act. The Terms of Reference were published on the same date and are attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Terms of Reference set out that the Inquiry must produce regular reports and an interim report by the end of 2018.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-20T10:45:43.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387696/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387696/answer","Terms of Reference.doc","Terms of reference","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387696/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the terms of reference of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse have been settled; whether the Inquiry will take place under the Inquiries Act 2005; and whether any time limits have been determined for the Inquiry to produce a report.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL1073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387697","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-07-20T15:25:11.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387697/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387697/answer","Lord Green Letter HL1074.pdf","UK Statistics Reply ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387697/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-06","Households","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the change in the number of households in the United Kingdom between 2010 and 2014 where (1) the Household Reference Person was born in the United Kingdom and (2) the Household Reference Person was not born in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL1074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387698","Home Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>A non-EU citizen who is not a family member of an EU citizen is required to present a valid national passport or other document which satisfactorily establishes identity and nationality and where required by the Immigration Rules additionally a UK visa or evidence of Leave to Remain in order to enter and reside in the UK.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-14T13:09:47.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387698/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387698/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","Immigration: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what documentation a non-European Union citizen resident in another EU country requires in order to (1) enter, and (2) reside in, the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL1075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387699","Home Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>A non-EU citizen who is a family member of an EU citizen is required to present a valid national passport or other document which satisfactorily establishes identity and nationality along with evidence of their right to enter and reside in the UK as required by the Immigration (European Economic Area) Regulations 2006.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-14T13:09:59.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387699/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387699/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","Immigration: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what documentation a non-European Union citizen who is resident in another EU country, and is a family member of an EU citizen, requires to (1) enter, and (2) reside in, the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL1076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387700","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), has not raised this particular issue with the President of Burma. While Burma has undergone a remarkable period of reform since the current government took power in 2011, we remain extremely concerned by allegations of historic human rights violations by the Burmese military. The UK is a strong supporter of the principle that there should be no impunity for the perpetrators of the most serious crimes. Any judgement on whether specific international crimes have occurred is a matter for international judicial decision rather than for governments or non-judicial bodies. There are a number of different models for moving on from conflict and ending impunity, and it is for the people of Burma, through their political representatives, to decide on the best model for their country.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-13T13:28:50.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387700/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387700/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","Burma: War Crimes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs has raised with the President of Burma concerns regarding evidence of war crimes committed by the Burmese Home Affairs Minister.","false","Biography information for Baroness Goudie",,"Baroness Goudie","HL1077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387701","Home Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Government is committed to maintaining a safe, secure and effective border. This includes a rigorous system of checks upon arrival. The Home Secretary and French Interior Minister Bernard Cazeneuve set out a number of commitments in a joint declaration, on 20 September 2014, to tackle problems at the port of Calais. This included £12 millio from the UK Government to help reinforce security.</p><p>We continue to work with the French Government to implement the practical solutions that have been agreed. On 2 July, the Home Secretary and the French Interior Minister reaffirmed the determination of both countries to strengthen and complete their joint strategy to deal with this common challenge, including by increasing the intervention fund to secure access to the Channel Tunnel. We are also addressing the factors that pull illegal immigration to the UK, through the Immigration Act 2014. The Act puts the law firmly on the side of those who respect it, not those who break it. It does this by stopping migrants using public services to which they are not entitled, reducing the pull factors which encourage people to come to the UK for the wrong reasons, and making it easier to remove people who should not be here.</p><p>The UK is also playing a leading role in pushing for comprehensive, long-term action through the EU and the UN to tackle the causes of illegal immigration and the organised trafficking gangs behind it, as well as increasing support and protection for those who need it in North and East Africa. Above all, we need to break the link between getting on a boat and achieving residence in Europe.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-14T13:11:02.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387701/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387701/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","Illegal Immigrants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they plan to tighten control of illegal immigration, in particular in the light of recent events at Calais.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL1078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387702","Home Office","false","2015-07-16","<p>The Government’s position on DFT was set out in the Written Ministerial Statement laid on 2 July:</p><p><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm150702/wmstext/150702m0001.htm" target="_blank">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201516/cmhansrd/cm150702/wmstext/150702m0001.htm</a></p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-16T12:56:53.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387702/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387702/answer","Home Department WMS - 2nd July.doc","WMS - 2nd July","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387702/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","Asylum: Detainees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to improve the fast-track detention system.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL1079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387703","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-21","<p>Advice on alternative sources of funding for international students not eligible for UK Government support is provided on the Education UK website. The website lists a range of scholarships and funding schemes that are administered by the British Council as well as support available from individual UK HE institutions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-21T12:11:43.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387703/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387703/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Overseas Students: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what alternatives are currently available to international students who are ineligible for undergraduate student finance.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL1080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387704","Home Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>There are no government estimates on the number of illegal migrants currently living in the UK who entered the country on a visa. Any such estimation would be extremely difficult and there would be considerable uncertainty around it. Instead of producing such uncertain estimates, Her Majesty's Government is focusing on making it harder for people to live in the UK illegally and has introduced exit checks, which over time, will improve the ability to identify individuals who have overstayed.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-13T14:40:10.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387704/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387704/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","Illegal Immigrants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the proportion of illegal migrants living in the United Kingdom who entered the United Kingdom on a visa.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL1081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387705","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","true","2015-07-16","<p><ins class="ministerial">The UK welcomes genuine international students and there is no cap on the number that can </ins>study here. The Government promotes study in the UK through the Britain is GREAT marketing campaign and through the British Council, which promotes UK education in over 100 countries, connecting millions of people with the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government also has major education agreements with overseas partners. Key programmes include the UK-China Partners in Education Programme, the UK-India Education Research Initiative and engagement in Brazil’s ‘Science without Borders’ scholarship scheme. It has also tripled funding (to £48m) in 2014/15 for Chevening scholarships for international students with leadership potential.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Government also supports student exchange, such as through the Erasmus Scheme, which enables international students to take short placements in the UK and British students to gain valuable overseas experience.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-16T13:03:31.463Z","2015-07-17T10:31:32.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387705/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387705/answer",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387705/answer/previousversion/15383","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Overseas Students","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that overseas students continue to consider studying in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL1082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387706","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Information Commissioner’s Office’s (ICO) income from data protection fees and the corresponding amount remitted to the Consolidated Fund for the last six years is set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Data Protection Fee Income (£’000)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount remitted to the Consolidated fund (£’000)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>17,519</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>16,528</p></td><td><p>781</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>16,055</p></td><td><p>359</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>15,484</p></td><td><p>446</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>14,965</p></td><td><p>505</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>13,192</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The amount available to spend each year on data protection activities is dependent on the number of organisations that notify with the ICO. Income for 2015/16 is currently profiled to be £18.5M.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL1084","2015-07-20T16:43:16.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387706/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387706/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-06","Data Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in each of the last six years for which figures are available, how much income was received by the Information Commissioner's Office in respect of its data protection activities; how much of that was spent on such activities; and how much was remitted to the Consolidated Fund.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387707","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Information Commissioner’s Office’s (ICO) income from data protection fees and the corresponding amount remitted to the Consolidated Fund for the last six years is set out in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Data Protection Fee Income (£’000)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount remitted to the Consolidated fund (£’000)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>17,519</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>16,528</p></td><td><p>781</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>16,055</p></td><td><p>359</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>15,484</p></td><td><p>446</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>14,965</p></td><td><p>505</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>13,192</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The amount available to spend each year on data protection activities is dependent on the number of organisations that notify with the ICO. Income for 2015/16 is currently profiled to be £18.5M.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL1083","2015-07-20T16:43:17.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387707/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387707/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-06","Data Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much the Information Commissioner's Office will be entitled to spend on data protection activities in the next financial year; and how that figure will be affected if the Information Commissioner's Office registration fee income increases.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387708","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Data Protection Act 1998 requires every data controller who is processing personal information to register with the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) unless they are exempt. The ICO’s website sets out the criteria for notification and provides guidance on the level of fee organisations should be paying. The ICO have also made it easier for organisations to notify and pay the fee by introducing online payments.</p><p> </p><p>At the end of 2014/15 there were 409,000 data controllers registered with the ICO which generated a total income of £17,519,000.</p><p> </p><p>It is for data controllers to seek registration; the ICO periodically reminds organisations of the requirement to notify.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL1087 ; HL1088","2015-07-20T16:51:20.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387708/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387708/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-06","Data Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps, including review, audit or other assessment, have been taken by (1) the Ministry of Justice, (2) the Information Commissioner's Office, and (3) any external auditors and advisers, to ensure that every data controller that processes personal information has (a) registered with the Information Commissioner, if required to, (b) paid the correct registration fee in accordance with the tiered structure, and (c) not processed any personal data if it has not registered.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387709","Department of Health","false","2015-07-20","<p>NHS England has advised that pemetrexed (Alimta) for maintenance treatment of stage IIIB/IV non-squamous non-small cell lung cancer after response to pemetrexed-containing first line therapy will be reviewed by the national Cancer Drug Fund (CDF) panel at its next meeting at the end of July 2015. It will remain on the national CDF list for that indication pending the outcome of that further review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Pemetrexed remains available for those patients who meet the criteria set out in the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence’s technology appraisal guidance on pemetrexed for the treatment of malignant pleural mesothelioma (TA135).</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-20T10:39:14.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387709/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387709/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Mesothelioma: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, following the decision by the panel of the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF) that the clinical benefits of pemetrexed as a maintenance treatment in patients with locally advanced or metastatic non-squamous non-small cell lung cancer, and who had previously not progressed on chemotherapy with the combination of cisplatin and pemetrexed, were insufficient to justify retaining pemetrexed within the CDF, pemetrexed will be withdrawn as a treatment option for patients with mesothelioma.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387710","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Data Protection Act 1998 requires every data controller who is processing personal information to register with the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) unless they are exempt. The ICO’s website sets out the criteria for notification and provides guidance on the level of fee organisations should be paying. The ICO have also made it easier for organisations to notify and pay the fee by introducing online payments.</p><p> </p><p>At the end of 2014/15 there were 409,000 data controllers registered with the ICO which generated a total income of £17,519,000.</p><p> </p><p>It is for data controllers to seek registration; the ICO periodically reminds organisations of the requirement to notify.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL1085 ; HL1088","2015-07-20T16:51:21.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387710/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387710/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-06","Data Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many data controllers were registered with the Information Commissioner’s Office on the most recent date for which figures are available; what income was generated from those organisations' registration fees; and what is their estimate of the annual and total income lost by non-registration.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387711","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Data Protection Act 1998 requires every data controller who is processing personal information to register with the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO) unless they are exempt. The ICO’s website sets out the criteria for notification and provides guidance on the level of fee organisations should be paying. The ICO have also made it easier for organisations to notify and pay the fee by introducing online payments.</p><p> </p><p>At the end of 2014/15 there were 409,000 data controllers registered with the ICO which generated a total income of £17,519,000.</p><p> </p><p>It is for data controllers to seek registration; the ICO periodically reminds organisations of the requirement to notify.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","HL1085 ; HL1087","2015-07-20T16:51:21.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387711/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387711/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-06","Data Protection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the number of data controllers who ought to have registered with the Information Commissioner’s Office but have not done so; and what steps have been and will be taken by (1) the Information Commissioner’s Office, and (2) the Ministry of Justice, to secure compliance with the statutory obligation to register.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387712","Department of Health","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) takes every precaution to ensure compliance with legislation and that identifiable data is not disclosed without a legal basis to do so. There are strict controls set out within the Data Protection Act that govern the disclosure of sensitive data.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>In all scenarios involving patient’s health data being wrongly disclosed, irrespective of the personal circumstances of a patient, HSCIC would seek to ensure appropriate reporting, investigations and corrective actions took place.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1090","2015-07-20T10:38:41.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387712/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387712/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Gender Recognition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps are being taken to ensure that the Health and Social Care Information Centre informs transsexual patients whose health data has been wrongly disclosed to third parties.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL1089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387713","Department of Health","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) takes every precaution to ensure compliance with legislation and that identifiable data is not disclosed without a legal basis to do so. There are strict controls set out within the Data Protection Act that govern the disclosure of sensitive data.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>In all scenarios involving patient’s health data being wrongly disclosed, irrespective of the personal circumstances of a patient, HSCIC would seek to ensure appropriate reporting, investigations and corrective actions took place.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1089","2015-07-20T10:38:42.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387713/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387713/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Gender Recognition","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that the Health and Social Care Information Centre does not contravene section 22 of the Gender Recognition Act 2004.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL1090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387714","Home Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Home Office advertised the tender opportunity using a contract notice on the TED (Tenders Electronic Daily - the online version of the 'Supplement to the Official Journal of the European Union', dedicated to European public procurement). The Home Office followed the principles of the Open Procedure. There were 22 providers who were invited to tender.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-13T14:42:18.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387714/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387714/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","British Nationality: English Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 30 June (HL705), whether the competitive procurement exercise that secured two Concession Service Providers of English language testing in the United Kingdom, and one for overseas, was subject to an open tender process; and if not, what was the nature of the competitive procurement process, and how many providers were invited to tender.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387715","Home Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>Four organisations tendered for the Secure English Language Testing competitive procurement exercise.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-15T16:07:09.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387715/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387715/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","British Nationality: English Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 30 June (HL705), how many organisations tendered in the competitive procurement exercise that secured two Concession Service Providers of English language testing in the United Kingdom, and one overseas.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387716","Home Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>There are no plans to publish the independent review into the provision of English Language testing.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-13T14:43:22.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387716/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387716/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","British Nationality: English Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to publish the report of the independent review into the provision of English language testing.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387717","Department of Health","false","2015-07-14","<p>Monitor use agency staff to temporarily fill administrative and clerical roles according to the business needs of the organisation, providing cover for vacancy, holiday and sickness.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The table below shows Monitor’s approximate average headcount for agency staff between 2010-11 and 2014-15. The total cost over this period was £1.564 million including VAT.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To note, there is some discrepancy in the data as collection methodology changed in 2011, when it started to be collected monthly.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Figures for headcount and spend on agency staff:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Average Headcount</p></td><td><p>Cost, £000 incl VAT</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>5.5</p></td><td><p>160**</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>235**</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>385*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>12.5</p></td><td><p>418</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>10.5</p></td><td><p>366</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Sum</p></td><td><p>50</p></td><td><p>1,564</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>313</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>* Extrapolation of full year position from incomplete data</p><p> </p><p>** Extrapolation based on trends</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-14T15:28:39.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387717/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387717/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Monitor: Employment Agencies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many agency staff Monitor has used since 2010; and at what cost.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387718","Department of Health","false","2015-07-20","<p>This Government is determined to reduce expensive staffing agency costs in the National Health Service.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Monitor’s project will look at how best to reduce this spend and enable the NHS to set up systems to deliver savings.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Spending on temporary staff in the NHS was £2.4 billion in 2013-14. In contrast, this initial work, led by Monitor, will cost £175,000 (excluding VAT) and could lead to substantive appointments being made to take the work forwards if required.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-20T10:39:45.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387718/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387718/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Monitor: Temporary Employment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of Monitor’s use of temporary staff to work with NHS Foundation Trusts on reducing agency staff costs as a model for the National Health Service.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387719","Department of Health","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Department has not received any specific representations from Monitor regarding increasing the number of training places for doctors and nurses.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Health Education England (HEE) is responsible for workforce planning for the National Health Service and as part of that process liaise with all arms length bodies, including Monitor, individual healthcare providers and key stakeholders regards medical and non medical staffing requirements going forward.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department set up HEE to deliver a better health and healthcare workforce for England. HEE is responsible for ensuring a secure workforce supply for the future balancing need against demand, taking into account factors such as the age profile of the existing workforce, the impact of technology, and new drugs.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-20T10:41:02.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387719/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387719/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Health Professions: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have received from Monitor regarding the case for increasing training places for doctors and nurses since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387720","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-16","<p>The Secretary of State for International Development and I, champion this issue every day as part of the department’s broader plan to improve the prospects of women and girls overseas. Gender is mainstreamed across all DFID programmes and we are proud of the impact the department has achieved in tackling violence against women and girls, not least through the 2014 Girl Summit which focused on eradicating Female Genital Mutilation and Early and Forced Child Marriage.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-07-16T16:18:50.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387720/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387720/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-06","Crimes of Violence: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have plans to appoint an International Violence Against Women Champion.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL1097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387721","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>We are delighted that the Girl Summit has accelerated international momentum on ending FGM and Child, Early and Forced Marriage. We have already seen follow-up events take place in Uganda, Bangladesh and Ethiopia and the African Union plan to host a Girl Summit later this year. Since the 2014 Girl Summit, the Department for International Development has focused on delivering the UK Government’s commitment to supporting an end to FGM and Child, Early and Forced Marriage globally, through its £35million programme on ending FGM and the recently launched £36million programme to accelerate action to end Child marriage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Domestically, a number of measures have been taken to strengthen the law on FGM through the Serious Crime Act, £1.6million has been committed for the next stage of the Department of Health’s FGM prevention programme, and an FGM Unit has been established and commenced a programme of outreach.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-07-15T15:06:22.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387721/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387721/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-06","Females: Equality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they are following up the Girl Summit 2014 in order to counter early marriage and Female Genital Mutilation; and how they plan to ensure that there is continued global momentum on those issues.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL1098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387722","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-15","<p>The Girl Summit, co-hosted with UNICEF in London in July 2014, secured over 180 commitments, including 43 governments. We are working with UNICEF to follow up with governments and other participants on progress since the Summit. A summary of these achievements will be available for the anniversary of the Summit.</p><p> </p><p>Over the last year the UK Government has also been working with UN partners, civil society and national Governments, including the Government of Bangladesh, to support countries to implement these commitments. Bangladesh held its own Girl Summit in October 2014, are making legal revisions to the 1929 Child Marriage Restraint Act and finalising the National Plan of Action for Ending Child Marriage.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-07-15T15:07:00.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387722/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387722/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-06","Bangladesh: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they are ensuring that pledges made at the Girl Summit 2014 by other countries, and in particular Bangladesh, are being met.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hodgson of Abinger",,"Baroness Hodgson of Abinger","HL1099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387723","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-08","<p>The senior-level steering board on Women, Peace and Security was established in April 2015. The Board will meet every six months; its first meeting was in April 2015 and the second will be held in September 2015.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-07-08T15:30:33.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387723/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387723/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387723/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-06","Conflict Resolution: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 30 June (HL698), when the steering board on Women, Peace and Security was established; and on how many occasions it has met.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387724","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>The UK has successfully ensured the Preventing Sexual Violence Initiative (PSVI) and UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 1325 is firmly on the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO) agenda with broad support from other NATO Allies. Earlier this year, our efforts helped create detailed NATO guidelines on the prevention of and response to conflict related sexual and gender based violence. These guidelines will be integrated into the education, training, operational planning, conduct of operations and evaluation of NATO led operations, as appropriate. Their overall aim is to reduce the risk of conflict related sexual violence and improve response measures that take protection needs into consideration. We support the work of the NATO Special Representative on Women, Peace and Security in implementing the NATO Policy and Action Plan. We will continue to take opportunities to promote PSVI and UNSCR 1325 in NATO as and when they arise.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-15T12:36:49.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387724/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387724/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","NATO","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Preventing Sexual Violence Initiative and UN Security Council Resolution 1325 remain priority work areas for the United Kingdom delegation to NATO.","false","Biography information for Baroness Helic",,"Baroness Helic","HL1101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387725","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-20","<p>The staffing numbers for the Prime Minister’s Office are included in the overall Cabinet Office staff numbers which are available on gov.uk from 2011 onwards.</p><p>The information prior to this point is not held centrally and it would incur disproportionate costs to be able to identify, analyse and provide this information before 2011.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-07-20T15:41:16.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387725/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387725/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-06","Prime Minister: Staff","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many staff there were in the Prime Minister's office for each Prime Minister over the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Lord Lawson of Blaby",,"Lord Lawson of Blaby","HL1102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387726","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-14","<p>In June 2015, there were 45 unlawful incursions by Spanish State vessels into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters (BGTW). The Royal Navy challenges all unlawful incursions. The United Kingdom also makes diplomatic protests to Spain in respect of these unlawful incursions, which are in violation of international law. These unlawful incursions are violations of, rather than threats to, UK sovereignty over BGTW.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-07-14T15:22:10.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387726/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387726/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-06","Gibraltar: Spain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many incursions into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters by Spanish vessels there were in June.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL1103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387727","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>From 1 June to 8 July, the British Government has sent five diplomatic protests by Note Verbale to the Government of Spain concerning 55 unlawful incursions by Spanish State vessels into British Gibraltar Territorial Waters. On 3 July, the Government protested at a senior level in Madrid following the unlawful incursion by a Spanish survey vessel, which struck a Royal Navy vessel with its probe. This incursion was also protested by Note Verbale.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-15T12:37:21.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387727/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387727/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","Gibraltar: Spain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations have been made to the government of Spain since 1 June regarding infringements of British Gibraltar Territorial Waters.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL1104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387728","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Government has published a BBC Charter Review consultation paper, seeking views on all aspects of the BBC, including its funding. A copy of this document has been deposited in the libraries of both Houses, and it is available online: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/bbc-charter-review-public-consultation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/bbc-charter-review-public-consultation</a></p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-20T13:33:24.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387728/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387728/answer","DCMS BBC Charter Review_AW (1) (1).pdf","BBC Charter Review: Public consultation 2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387728/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","BBC Monitoring: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they plan to take to protect the funding presently available for the BBC Monitoring Service in the light of the reduction in the BBC's overall funding.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL1105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387729","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>The number of taskings of helicopters from the Republic of Ireland to assist HM Coastguard both in maritime and inland incidents in Northern Ireland in each of the years 2010 to 2014 is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>48</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>41</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>26</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-07-14T11:25:47.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387729/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387729/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387729/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-07-06","Rescue Services: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Dunlop on 30 June (HL756), in each of the years 2010 to 2014, on how many occasions an air-rescue helicopter was flown from the Republic of Ireland to Northern Ireland to aid civil authorities.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL1106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387730","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>The number of taskings of helicopters from Great Britain to assist HM Coastguard both in maritime and inland incidents in Northern Ireland in each of the years 2010 to 2014 is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2015-07-14T11:26:09.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387730/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387730/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387730/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-07-06","Rescue Services: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Dunlop on 30 June (HL755), in each of the years 2010 to 2014, on how many occasions an air-rescue helicopter was flown from the mainland to Northern Ireland to aid civil authorities.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL1107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387731","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Deposit Guarantee Scheme Directive (DGSD) updates existing EU legislation designed to harmonise the level of deposit protection provided across the European Economic Area (EEA).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This is necessary to ensure that depositors are entitled to the same level of protection wherever they deposit their money, and that UK firms are not competitively disadvantaged in relation to firms in other EEA jurisdictions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As a result of the current strength of the pound in relation to the euro, it has been necessary for the Prudential Regulation Authority to review the sterling coverage limit. However, the Government has taken action to ensure that UK depositors are not exposed to a sudden reduction in the level of protection they receive.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has laid a statutory instrument to ensure that depositors who are currently entitled to £85,000 of protection from the Financial Services Compensation Scheme will continue to be until 31 December 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This will ensure that there is sufficient time available for depositors to be made aware of the changes, and to take such steps as they feel necessary to manage their financial affairs appropriately in light of this change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-07-20T16:37:43.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387731/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387731/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Financial Services Compensation Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will explain why they agreed to a European directive tying the United Kingdom's bank deposit protection scheme to the euro-sterling value which has resulted in a £10,000 reduction in the level of protection for United Kingdom depositors from next year; and what action they intend to take to address this anomaly.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL1108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387732","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Government is finalising the schedule for reviewing arm's-length bodies in this parliament. In the period 2010-15 the Government reduced the number of public bodies by a third, reducing administrative costs by over £2.6bn.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2015-07-20T15:24:23.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387732/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387732/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-06","Public Bodies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bridges of Headley on 16 June (HL204) concerning non-departmental public bodies and executive agencies, whether they intend to (1) make further cost savings, and (2) reduce the number of agencies, in the period 2015 to 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL1109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387733","Home Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>I refer to my previous written answer: disclosure of such information could compromise the integrity of and affect the security of the individuals concerned. Disclosing such details would not only reveal tactical policing decisions, but would compromise the safety of those arrangements since it would enable those wishing to circumvent them to form an assessment of the level of policing and protection being provided. Decisions about the protective security of former Prime Ministers abroad are made by the Cabinet Office chaired, Royal and Ministerial Visits Committee for Overseas Travel.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-07-14T13:26:42.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387733/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387733/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-06","Former Prime Ministers: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 25 June (HL714), why information about the cost of security protection for former Prime Ministers and Deputy Prime Ministers could compromise the security of the individuals concerned; and whether such security protection extends to when they are abroad.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL1110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387734","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-07-20","<p>Currently, there are no plans to review extant Acts of Parliament to ensure that the right of freedom of expression is not being restricted.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will be bringing forward proposals for a Bill of Rights to protect fundamental human rights, but also prevent their abuse and restore some common sense to the system.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-07-20T10:49:31.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387734/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387734/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-06","Freedom of Expression","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Faulks on 1 July (HL561), whether they plan to review extant Acts of Parliament to ensure that the right of freedom of expression is not being restricted.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL1111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387735","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>All non-nuclear weapon States party to the Non-Proliferation Treaty, including Saudi Arabia and Iran, have an obligation not to manufacture or otherwise acquire nuclear weapons, and to enter into a Comprehensive Safeguards Agreement with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) to enable international verification of the fulfilment of this obligation. The UK continues to encourage all those States that have not yet done so to bring into force an Additional Protocol to their Safeguards Agreement to give the IAEA additional information on their nuclear programmes and expanded powers of access to their nuclear activities.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-15T12:37:56.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387735/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387735/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","Saudi Arabia: Nuclear Power","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 3 July (HL718), whether they intend to apply the same conditions under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) framework to Saudi Arabia as those applied to Iran, which is also a signatory of the NPT.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL1112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387736","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-20","<p>On the 9<sup>th</sup> July, the EU Parliament considered a non-legislative own initiative report from the Legal Affairs Committee (JURI) on EU copyright reform, and voted against proposals to restrict individuals’ freedom to photograph or film buildings or statues located in public places.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-07-20T12:23:08.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387736/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387736/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Copyright","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 6 July (HL934) concerning the proposal by the European Parliament for restrictions on photographs or video footage of public buildings, whether they have the power of veto over such draft legislation; and if so, whether they plan to use their veto in this instance.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL1113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387737","Department of Health","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Government has not given consideration to reducing the use of folic acid supplementation by women of child-bearing age.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To reduce the risk of neural tube defect affected pregnancies, all women who could become pregnant are advised to take an additional 400μg/day folic acid as a medicinal or food supplement prior to conception and until the twelfth week of pregnancy.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-20T10:41:30.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387737/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387737/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Folic Acid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to reducing the use of folic supplementation by women of child-bearing age.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL1114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387738","Department of Health","false","2015-07-20","<p>Public Health England is not aware of any evidence to suggest that a folic acid deficiency in men may lead to birth defects in their offspring.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-20T10:41:44.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387738/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387738/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Folic Acid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any recent evidence that a folic acid deficiency in men may lead to birth defects in their offspring.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL1115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387739","Department of Health","false","2015-07-20","<p>Serum total folate concentrations were published in a National Diet and Nutrition Survey Supplementary Report on 20 March 2015, available at the following link and has also been attached.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-diet-and-nutrition-survey-supplementary-report-blood-folate" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/national-diet-and-nutrition-survey-supplementary-report-blood-folate</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For women of child bearing age (16 to 49 years) in the United Kingdom, mean serum total folate concentration was 20.0 nmol/L, 16.5% had concentrations below 10 nmol/L, the World Health Organization (WHO) threshold indicating biochemical folate deficiency.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-07-20T10:42:49.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387739/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387739/answer","NDNS_Y1_4_Folate_report.pdf","Folate Report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387739/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Folic Acid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what were the serum folate levels in women of child-bearing age in the latest results of the National Diet and Nutrition Survey; and how these compare to the World Health Organisation thresholds.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL1116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387740","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Ministry of Defence has received £28.8 million for the marginal costs associated with providing humanitarian assistance in Sierra Leone. While costs are still being refined, the Ministry of Defence expects to receive up to £5 million for marginal costs incurred in support to the Nepal earthquake relief, and up to £11 million for costs associated with the deployment of HMS Bulwark and Merlin helicopters to the Mediterranean for search and rescue activities.</p><p>As there is a standing arrangement for the Ministry of Defence to recover the marginal costs associated with support to humanitarian assistance and disaster relief, the total costs are not available.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-07-14T15:25:31.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387740/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387740/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387740/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-06","Military Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 1 July (HL754), what marginal cost amounts will be credited to the defence budget for providing such humanitarian assistance in Sierra Leone, Nepal and the Mediterranean; and, in each case, what percentage of the total cost of this assistance to the defence budget those marginal costs represent.","false","Biography information for Lord Craig of Radley",,"Lord Craig of Radley","HL1117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387741","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-20","<p>The Secretary of State received a letter from Ekklesia dated 3 July 2015, which was subsequently published online in the Tablet.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State has responded to this letter from Ekklesia.</p><p> </p><p>It would not be appropriate for us to make public our response to this private correspondence.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-07-20T15:23:55.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387741/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387741/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387741/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-06","Welfare State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the open letter to the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions published in the Tablet on 4 July.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387742","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-13","<p /> <p>There are no current plans to replace benefit sanctions with community service.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2015-07-13T15:52:12.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387742/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387742/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387742/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-06","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to replace benefit sanctions with community service, for those who are unemployed, disabled or in chronic bad health.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387743","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-15","<p>The Government wants to move from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society. As the Chancellor announced at the Summer Budget, a new National Living Wage (NLW) will be introduced from April 2016. This will apply to all people over the age of 25, and will directly benefit 2¾ million people.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>At the same time, the government is increasing the employer National Insurance Contributions (NICs) employment allowance from £2000 to £3000. This will reduce the costs of employment for businesses and charities and will mean that a business can employ four people full time on NLW and pay no employer NICs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-07-15T15:18:04.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387743/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387743/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387743/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Living Wage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to provide tax incentives to firms and employers paying the living wage to all their workers.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387744","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-15","<p>Decisions about food sourcing must be taken by individual businesses. However, last year the Government published the ‘Plan for Public Procurement of Food and Catering Services’, through which the public sector demonstrates leadership in the better procurement of local and sustainable food. The Plan also helps suppliers of British grown and processed produce to take advantage of opportunities to supply the public sector. Several companies are adopting this approach across their wider operations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, we are putting in place an ambitious 25 year plan to promote and grow our world-leading food and farming industry, encouraging enterprise and boosting productivity at each stage of the food chain.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-07-15T11:25:27.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387744/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387744/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387744/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-06","Food: Procurement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to encourage companies based in the United Kingdom to source produce from local suppliers.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Shrewsbury",,"The Earl of Shrewsbury","HL1121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387745","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-16","<p>The Government has supported installation of 60,756 chargepoints for plug-in vehicles, including those for domestic use, in the last 10 years. A significant number of chargepoints are being installed without Government funding. Data on all public chargepoints is collected in the National Charge Point Registry.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This Government is aiming for almost every car and van to be a zero emission vehicle by 2050, and we have pledged £500 million over the next five years to achieve this. Further details of this investment will be announced in due course. The Electric Vehicle Homecharge Scheme is currently funding domestic chargepoints for ultra low emission vehicle motorists.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-07-16T12:57:45.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387745/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387745/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387745/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-06","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many charging points for electric vehicles there are across the United Kingdom; and whether they have any proposals for increasing this number.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Shrewsbury",,"The Earl of Shrewsbury","HL1122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387746","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Climate Change Act 2008 introduced a target for the UK to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by at least 80%, based on 1990 levels. This followed advice from the Committee on Climate Change who deemed that 80% was a fair share from the UK to an international effort to limit global warming to 2 degrees.</p><p>Our policies are designed to tackle climate change and make the transition to a low carbon economy. This includes:</p><p> </p><p>· Helping consumers and businesses to save money on their energy bills</p><p> </p><p>· Making homes more energy efficient</p><p> </p><p>· Helping consumers to take control of their energy use with smart meters</p><p> </p><p>· Decarbonising the power sector in the most cost effective way</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2015-07-13T16:13:17.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387746/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387746/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387746/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-06","Climate Change","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what their plans are to fight climate change.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Shrewsbury",,"The Earl of Shrewsbury","HL1123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387747","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-15","<p>In 2014 the contribution to the economy of UK agriculture, as measured by gross value added at basic price, was £9.2 billion.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of people employed on agricultural holdings in the UK on 1st June 2014 was 181,000. This includes salaried managers, regular and casual workers.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>An additional 294,000 self-employed principal farmers also worked on agricultural holdings in the UK, giving a total of 476,000 or 1.43% of the total UK workforce.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Table 1: The number of people working on farms in the UK June 2014</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Number of people ('000 head)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Salaried managers, regular and casual workers</p></td><td><p>181</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Principal farmers, partners, directors and spouses</p></td><td><p>294</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total number of people working on farms</p></td><td><p>476</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-07-15T11:26:27.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387747/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387747/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387747/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-06","Agriculture","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the economic value of the agricultural sector to the economy; and how many jobs it provides.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Shrewsbury",,"The Earl of Shrewsbury","HL1124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387748","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-14","<p>We are not participating directly in Saudi-led military operations in Yemen, but we are providing technical support, precision-guided weapons and exchanging information with the Saudi Arabian armed forces through pre-existing arrangements.</p><p>In addition to the personnel who continue to provide support for equipment supplied, we have a small number of liaison personnel in Saudi and coalition air and maritime headquarters. This includes personnel in the Maritime Coalition Coordination Centre in the region supporting the delivery of humanitarian aid into Yemen.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-07-14T15:25:56.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387748/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387748/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387748/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-06","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what support the United Kingdom is providing to the government of Saudi Arabia in its military campaign in Yemen.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL1125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387749","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-20","<p>The government has secured a deal that protects UK taxpayers from any risk from financing euro area bailouts now and in the future. This deal gives legal force to the commitment secured in 2010 that UK taxpayers would not be drawn into a euro area bailout. While Greece remains in the euro, its financial stability is the responsibility of the euro area.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-07-20T16:38:41.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387749/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387749/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387749/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Economic Situation: Greece","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the cost to the public purse resulting from the economic crisis in Greece.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL1126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387750","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-13","<p>Her Majesty’s Government is not able to make an estimate of the amount of new railway line to be laid by 2020. However, the Government is supporting £38billion of Network Rail spend from 2014/15 to 2018/19 and this includes £13billion on enhancements and £12billion on renewing life expired parts of the network.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-07-13T10:52:07.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387750/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387750/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387750/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-06","Railway Track","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many miles of new railway line they estimate will have been laid in the United Kingdom by 2020.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL1127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387751","Attorney General","false","2015-07-17","<p>Proscription is an important means of disrupting terrorist organisations in the UK. The Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) also known as The Islamic State of Iraq al-Sham (ISIS) was proscribed as a terrorist organization in the UK with effect from 20 June 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Section 13 of the Terrorism Act 2000 provides that a person commits an offence if he, in a public place, wears an item of clothing or wears, carries or displays article in such a way or in such circumstances as to arouse reasonable suspicion that he is a member or supporter of a proscribed organisation. Flags would come within the definition of “article”. This is a summary only offence carrying a maximum of six months imprisonment or a fine.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To date there have been no prosecutions in England and Wales as a result of displaying a flag in such a way or in such circumstances as to arouse reasonable suspicion that the person displaying it is a member or supporter of ISIL. A black flag of the type associated with ISIL has featured in a number of prosecutions of individuals for more serious terrorist offences.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2015-07-17T12:22:22.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387751/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387751/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387751/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-07-06","Islamic State: Flags","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prosecutions there have been as a result of displaying the ISIL flag in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL1128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387752","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>Our Ambassador to Libya is currently based in Tunis.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-13T13:29:00.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387752/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387752/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387752/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","Libya: Diplomatic Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government where the British Ambassador to Libya is currently based.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL1129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387753","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-15","<p>We are not aware of any incidents of civilian casualties as a result of UK strike activity over Iraq. Our overriding concern in conducting such strikes is to protect innocent civilians from the terrorists we would wish to target. Therefore, we take every possible measure to avoid any civilian casualties. If at any time civilian casualties were thought to have occurred, any estimates of numbers would be a matter for the coalition.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-07-15T15:12:43.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387753/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387753/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387753/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-06","Middle East: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of civilian casualties resulting from Allied bombing of ISIL targets in Iraq and Syria.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL1130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387754","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>The UK intervenes in every debate on the Chechnya cases in the Council of Europe’s Committee of Ministers. In conjunction with other Member States, we have submitted written questions on specific actions Russia has taken to implement judgements on Chechnya. We have raised the cases bilaterally with the Russian delegation in Strasbourg, pressing for full implementation. We are also regularly briefed on the Chechnya cases by human rights non-governmental organisations in Strasbourg, London and Moscow. We will continue to use the Committee of Ministers as a key forum for encouraging Russia to fully implement key judgements relating to the North Caucasus – a vital step to ending the climate of impunity in the region. The Council of Europe’s website holds further information on the status of Russia’s implementation of European Court of Human Rights judgements on Chechnya, together with details of all actions taken by the Committee of Ministers in their supervision of these judgements.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-13T13:29:57.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387754/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387754/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387754/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","Chechnya: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what actions they are taking in the Council of Europe's Committee of Ministers to ensure that Russia implements the rulings of the European Court of Human Rights on Chechnya; and how many of those rulings remain unimplemented.","false","Biography information for Lord Judd",,"Lord Judd","HL1131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387755","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>At the African Union (AU) Summit in June the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Rochford and Southend East (James Duddridge), discussed tackling irregular migration with a number of African ministers as well as the AU Commissioner for Peace and Security. He made clear our desire to work with African partners on a comprehensive solution to the migration crisis. The Summit Declaration reaffirmed the commitment by African governments to addressing irregular migration, including combating human trafficking and people smuggling.</p><p>The British Government will now work closely with EU and AU partners ahead of the Valletta Summit in November to develop proposals for action to disrupt smuggling and trafficking networks; strengthen cooperation on returns; and address the root causes of migration.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-15T12:39:11.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387755/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387755/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387755/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","Africa: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 17 June (HL214), what was the outcome of the meetings to discuss irregular migration at the African Union Summit in June.","false","Biography information for Lord Boateng",,"Lord Boateng","HL1132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387756","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Prime Minister, the European Commission and the US government have all confirmed that the EU-US Free Trade Agreement will pose no threat to the provision of key UK public services, such as NHS healthcare, and EU countries will be free to decide how they run their public health systems. The agreement could, however, benefit the UK economy by up to £10 billion a year in the long run, and should therefore benefit the public finances as well as businesses and workers. Small businesses in particular will benefit from removing unnecessary barriers to trade.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Maude of Horsham",,"2015-07-14T16:36:23.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387756/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387756/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387756/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the potential risks in the United Kingdom to (1) public health, (2) public finances, and (3) small businesses, from the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP); and whether they are considering any opt-outs from TTIP for any sectors likely to be damaged by the agreement.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL1133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387757","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-14","<p>The EU-US Free Trade Agreement is expected to be a mixed agreement to which the UK will individually be a party. In that case before it can come fully into force, it will be subject to agreement by each Member State. In the UK this does not require legislation, instead Parliament will receive the complete draft text of the agreement and can scrutinise it through debates in both Houses. We will not know for certain whether any implementing legislation will be necessary until the agreement is closer to completion.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Maude of Horsham",,"2015-07-14T16:31:42.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387757/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387757/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387757/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what legislation will have to be put before Parliament to give effect to the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership in the United Kingdom.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL1134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387758","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2015-07-20","<p>The second largest opposition party is neither formally defined nor given specific speaking rights by the Standing Orders of the House or the Companion to the Standing Orders. The Companion to Standing Orders does, however, set out several areas where the “opposition front benches” have the right to speak for longer than backbenchers or have rights to speak at specific points in proceedings.<br><br>Of the political parties represented in the House, only the Official Opposition and the Liberal Democrat group operate frontbenches of a size that permits them to shadow each Government department. It is for that reason that the definition of “opposition frontbenches” that applied in practice before the 2010 Parliament has been reverted to in this Parliament. <br><br>It remains open to any member who wishes to propose a change to current arrangements to make representations to me and/or make a submission to the Procedure Committee.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston","HL1136 ; HL1137 ; HL1138 ; HL1139 ; HL1588","2015-07-20T16:47:20.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387758/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387758/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387758/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2015-07-06","House of Lords: Parliamentary Procedure","2","House of Lords","To ask the Leader of the House whether the speaking rights of the second largest opposition party front bench in the House of Lords can be reallocated to the opposition party with the second highest votes cast at the last general election.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell-Savours",,"Lord Campbell-Savours","HL1135"
