"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387762","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2015-07-20","<p>The second largest opposition party is neither formally defined nor given specific speaking rights by the Standing Orders of the House or the Companion to the Standing Orders. The Companion to Standing Orders does, however, set out several areas where the “opposition front benches” have the right to speak for longer than backbenchers or have rights to speak at specific points in proceedings.<br><br>Of the political parties represented in the House, only the Official Opposition and the Liberal Democrat group operate frontbenches of a size that permits them to shadow each Government department. It is for that reason that the definition of “opposition frontbenches” that applied in practice before the 2010 Parliament has been reverted to in this Parliament. <br><br>It remains open to any member who wishes to propose a change to current arrangements to make representations to me and/or make a submission to the Procedure Committee.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston","HL1135 ; HL1136 ; HL1137 ; HL1138 ; HL1588","2015-07-20T16:47:20.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387762/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387762/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387762/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2015-07-06","House of Lords: Parliamentary Procedure","2","House of Lords","To ask the Leader of the House whether the percentage of the vote cast for a political party at a general election is a consideration in deciding whether a political party is granted opposition front-bench speaking rights in the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell-Savours",,"Lord Campbell-Savours","HL1139"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387763","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-17","<p>We remain concerned by all restrictions to freedom of religion or belief in China. Whilst Article 36 of the Chinese Constitution specifies that ‘Citizens of the People's Republic of China enjoy freedom of religious belief’, only five religions are officially recognised, and practice is subject to restrictions. <br><br>We regularly raise our concerns with the Chinese authorities, and did so in detail during the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue in April. We highlight our concerns in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Annual Report on Human Rights. Our concerns are also raised in international fora such as the UN Human Rights Council. <br><br>We regard freedom of thought, conscience and belief as a fundamental human right and will continue to raise our concerns as part of our broader relationship with China.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-17T11:50:25.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387763/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387763/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387763/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","China: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the persecution of the various religious communities in China.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL1140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387764","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>Although freedom of religion or belief is guaranteed under the Chinese constitution, we remain concerned about restrictions to this right. We continue to be concerned about the treatment of Muslims, in the Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region in particular, including restrictions on the celebration of Ramadan and Islamic dress. We regularly raise our concerns with the Chinese authorities.</p><p>China is bound, as a member of the UN Human Rights Council, to respect the international commitments to which it is a party, including those related to freedom of religion or belief. Freedom of religion or belief remains one of this Government’s core human rights priorities and we continue to support its development globally.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-15T12:40:10.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387764/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387764/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387764/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","China: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of suffering within the Uyghur communities and the pressure put on Muslims in China during the month of Ramadan.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL1141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387765","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-16","<p>We remain concerned by the human rights situation in China, not least all restrictions to freedom of religion or belief.</p><p>As a member of the UN Human Rights Council, China is bound to respect the international commitments to which it is a party. As such, we consistently call on China to ratify the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights – we last did so at the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue in April.</p><p>We continue to raise areas where we assess China’s actions are not in line with either its international human rights commitments or its own constitution. We highlight these, and our broader range of concerns, in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Annual Report on Human Rights and Democracy. We also make representations in international fora such as the UN Human Rights Council.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-16T15:05:23.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387765/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387765/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387765/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","China: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of alleged breaches of international law in China regarding the freedom of religion and freedom to worship without being harassed.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL1142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387766","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>We have not made any assessment of involvement of British Libyans in the overthrowing of Colonel Gaddaffi.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-07-15T12:40:24.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387766/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387766/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387766/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-06","Libya: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the involvement of British Libyans in the overthrowing of Colonel Gaddafi’s government; and if so, how many were involved; and how many of them were prosecuted.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL1143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387767","Attorney General","false","2015-07-13","<p>In the year to 31<sup>st </sup>December 2014, the Law Officers personally considered 469 cases and referred 128 offenders to the Court of Appeal under the unduly lenient sentence scheme. Leave was granted by the Court in 95% of cases which included some of the most serious violent and sexual offences, including murder, rape and sexual assault.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Attorney General’s Office publishes statistics for unduly lenient sentences at the end of the calendar year. This is to ensure that the figures are released in a consistent format and are accurate and quality assured. Unduly lenient sentences statistics for 2013 and 2014 are published on the Attorney General’s Office website - <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/attorney-generals-office" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/organisations/attorney-generals-office</a>.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2015-07-13T08:38:15.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387767/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387767/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387767/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2015-07-06","Sentencing: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, on how many occasions his Department has referred a criminal sentence to the Court of Appeal for review because it was felt to be unduly lenient in 2015.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","5701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387768","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-09","<p>The information related to numbers and costs of people engaged in delivering UKTI objectives are available in the annual report, page 58 on the link below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443633/UKTI-Annual-Report-Accounts-2014-2015-Web-Version.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443633/UKTI-Annual-Report-Accounts-2014-2015-Web-Version.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-09T15:46:47.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387768/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387768/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387768/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","UK Trade and Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, where each UKTI staff member is based; and at what civil service grade and salary band each such staff member is employed.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","5649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387769","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-09","<p>Ministers and officials hold numerous meetings with businesses and industry organisations to discuss a wide range of issues, including Europe.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is progressing with its renegotiation of our relationship with the EU, one focus of which will be increasing the EU’s economic competitiveness, ahead of a referendum on this issue.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-09T15:15:36.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387769/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387769/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387769/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations he has received from representatives of the industrial sector on the potential issues associated with the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","5650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387770","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-10","<p /> <p>The Government and its delivery partner the Medical Research Council (MRC), remains committed to open access to research publications in line with the recommendations of the 2012 Finch Group Report.</p><p> </p><p>Research Councils UK (RCUK) has published guidance agreed by all of the parties involved in the Finch Group. An independent panel set up by RCUK published a review of implementation of open access in March 2015, and later this summer RCUK will issue its response which will describe how the MRC and other research councils will address the issues identified. A UK Open Access Co-ordination Group was set up to inform and guide implementation of the changes, including publishers, funders, and other key interests.</p><p> </p><p>The research councils recognise access to underlying research data complements open access to research publications. RCUK recently published further guidance on best practice in the management of research data which applies to MRC funded research in universities, research organisations and the MRC’s own research units and institutes. The Government welcomes the production of a Concordat on Open Data agreed across the research community, which will be published this summer.</p><p> </p><p>Responsibility for managing technologies and other intellectual property resulting from MRC investments rests with the organisation that generates them. It is the responsibility of the research organisation, and all engaged in the research, to make every reasonable effort to ensure that the intellectual assets obtained in the course of the research are used to the benefit of society and the economy.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-07-10T12:29:08.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387770/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387770/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387770/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Medical Research Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure that technology and knowledge generated through Medical Research Council investments is open access.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","5711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387771","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-07-09","<p>At Budget 2014, the Chancellor announced that businesses located within the Executive’s proposed pilot Enterprise Zone near Coleraine will benefit from Enhanced Capital Allowances (ECAs) until 2020.</p><p>Implementing this measure is a matter for the Executive in Northern Ireland. I understand that work to finalise proposals is ongoing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-07-09T14:33:12.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387771/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387771/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387771/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-07-06","Enterprise Zones: Coleraine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of the effect on the local economy in Coleraine of the enterprise zone in that area.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","5736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387772","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-13","<p>Since 1 October 2013, 210 employers have been named under the National Minimum Wage naming scheme.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC has issued 333 Notices of Underpayment (NoUs) since 29 January 2015. Of these, 274 were for investigations that commenced on or after 1 October 2013 and are therefore eligible for naming under the new scheme.</p><p> </p><p>Since 29 January 2015, the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills has named 118 employers, of which 4 employers were issued an NoU after that date. The Department expects to name more employers shortly.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-13T11:56:27.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387772/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387772/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387772/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the Answer of 29 January 2015 to Question 221930, how many of the employers issued with a Notice of Underpayment of the National Minimum Wage have been named under the Department's revised national minimum wage naming and shaming scheme; how many employers have been issued with such a notice since 29 January 2015; and how many of those employers have been named under that scheme.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","5609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387773","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-14","<p>Food and drink companies in the UK have full access to the range of services offered by UK Trade and Investment. Our trade advisers work with companies across the UK to provide step by step advice and guidance on food and drink opportunities, working in tandem with our overseas network who identify export opportunities and support companies with specific projects.</p><p> </p><p>Support ranges from upskilling companies so they are export-ready (the Passport to Export Scheme), bespoke market intelligence (the Overseas Market Information Service), through to tailored missions and meet the buyer events, for example.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-14T11:48:25.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387773/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387773/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387773/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","UK Trade and Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what support UK Trade & Investment is providing to the food and drink industry.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","5616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387774","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-13","<p /> <p>We understand that the US does not currently have a direct equivalent to the EU Classification, Labelling and Packaging (CLP) Regulation. The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration, which covers hazards to people in the workplace, has adopted the United Nations Globally Harmonised System for classification and labelling of chemicals (GHS), which the CLP is modelled on. However, US Administrations that cover environment and consumer issues have not yet adopted the GHS. During the EU-US Free-Trade Agreement negotiations (TTIP), we will continue to support the EU’s objective to promote alignment in classification and labelling of chemicals in accordance with the GHS and will continue to press for an ambitious EU-US Free-Trade Agreement.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-13T14:03:55.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387774/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387774/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387774/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Hazardous Substances: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the differences between regulation (EC) No. 1272/2008 on classification, labelling and packaging of substances and mixtures and corresponding US law; how he plans to resolve any such differences in the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership; and what position the Government plans to take in negotiations on resolving such differences.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","5618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387775","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-14","<p>The total number of complaints against the Student Loans Company (SLC) in (a) 2012, (b) 2013 and (c) 2014 is set out in the table below. For information I have also provided the number of complaints expressed as a percentage of the total number of SLC’s customers in each corresponding year:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of complaints</p><p>lodged against SLC</p></td><td><p>Number of complaints as a percentage</p><p>of the total number of customers</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>a)</p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>11,085</p></td><td><p>0.19%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>b)</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>14,128</p></td><td><p>0.22%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>c)</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>14,235</p></td><td><p>0.21%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Please note that SLC tracks complaints rather than complainants. However these numbers indicate the number of complainants because it is rare for customers to raise complaints on separate issues in the same year.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2015-07-14T15:05:31.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387775/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387775/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387775/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Student Loans Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the total number of complainants lodging complaints against the Student Loans Company was in (a) 2012, (b) 2013 and (c) 2014.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","5621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387776","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-09","<p>This information is not held centrally and can only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>I am unable to comment on meetings held under the previous Government as it is an established convention that Ministers of one Administration cannot see the documents of a previous administration.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-09T15:45:33.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387776/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387776/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387776/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Bribery Act 2010","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what meetings (a) ministers and (b) officials from his Department have held with business organisations to discuss the Bribery Act 2010 and associated departmental guidance since January 2015; and on what dates such meetings were held.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","5635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387777","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-10","<p>All future spending decisions will be taken as part of the Spending Review.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-10T12:30:18.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387777/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387777/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387777/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-06","Adult Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will increase the adult skills budget to (a) increase the non-apprenticeship elements and (b) maintain funding for the apprenticeship element at current levels; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","5661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387778","Department of Health","false","2015-07-09","<p>The Prime Minister has written to government departments setting out his expectations on open data and transparency. Work is underway to take forward the transparency agenda nationally and internationally. This will cover diseases that are a threat to health security, for example emerging infectious diseases with pandemic potential.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-07-09T15:24:21.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387778/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387778/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387778/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-06","Clinical Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the announcement by the Prime Minister at the G7 Summit that all UK-funded clinical trials will be made openly available, what steps he is taking to require companies to publish such trials; and which diseases will be covered.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","5756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387779","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-09","<p>It is our policy to keep content published on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> available as a public record. Any content which is not current, or has been superseded, is clearly marked including Government-commissioned reports.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-07-09T11:17:26.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387779/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387779/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-06","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how members of the public can access Government-commissioned reports on the gov.uk website which have been archived.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","5759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387780","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>The July 2015 Financial Stability Report notes that buy-to-let mortgage lending now accounts for 15% of the stock of outstanding mortgages. The Financial Policy Committee have stated that they will continue to monitor this sector closely. In 2015, HM Treasury will publish a consultation on buy-to-let mortgage lending. The consultation will seek to build an in-depth evidence base on how the UK buy-to-let housing market may carry risks to financial stability.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","5659","2015-07-13T13:25:39.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387780/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387780/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans that his Department's consultation on the tools which the Financial Policy Committee may use in relation to buy-to-let mortgage lending will consider whether this type of lending should be regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority in the same way as residential mortgages.","true","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","5607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387781","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>The July 2015 Financial Stability Report notes that buy-to-let mortgage lending now accounts for 15% of the stock of outstanding mortgages. The Financial Policy Committee have stated that they will continue to monitor this sector closely. In 2015, HM Treasury will publish a consultation on buy-to-let mortgage lending. The consultation will seek to build an in-depth evidence base on how the UK buy-to-let housing market may carry risks to financial stability.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","5607","2015-07-13T13:25:39.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387781/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387781/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the finding of the Bank of England's Financial Stability Report of July 2015 regarding growth in buy-to-let mortgage lending and the potential risk to financial stability posed by such trends.","true","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","5659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387782","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-14","<p>The new pension flexibilities, which took effect on 6 April, allow people to have greater freedom and choice than ever before in how they spend their retirement savings.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Independent analysis indicates that the majority of pension pots are not large enough to have an impact on either buy to let mortgage approvals, or on house prices.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-14T16:17:27.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387782/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387782/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Annuities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of recent annuity reforms on (a) the buy-to-let mortgage market and (b) house prices.","true","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","5630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387783","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) launched the Let Property campaign in September 2013 with the objective of raising landlords’ awareness of the need to review their tax affairs to ensure they are in order. The campaign provides a voluntary disclosure opportunity to put right any previous errors or omissions, helping landlords to stay on track in future.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC will publish these figures in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","5632","2015-07-13T13:53:11.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387783/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387783/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Private Rented Housing: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many landlords have made a voluntary disclosure to HM Revenue and Customs through the Let Property Campaign in (a) the North West, (b) Lancashire and (c) Pendle constituency since that campaign began.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","5631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387784","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) launched the Let Property campaign in September 2013 with the objective of raising landlords’ awareness of the need to review their tax affairs to ensure they are in order. The campaign provides a voluntary disclosure opportunity to put right any previous errors or omissions, helping landlords to stay on track in future.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC will publish these figures in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","5631","2015-07-13T13:53:11.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387784/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387784/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Private Rented Housing: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects to be able to provide information about how much previously-undeclared income has been declared as a result of the Let Property Campaign.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","5632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387785","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-09","<p>This information is published as Official Statistics together with the Inheritance Tax National Statistics at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/inheritance-tax-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/inheritance-tax-statistics</a>.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-07-09T15:26:03.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387785/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387785/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Inheritance Tax: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people with post codes in Wales paid inheritance tax in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","5737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387786","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>Working Tax Credit provides financial support to those families on low incomes and Child Tax Credit assists families on low or no income with the additional costs of raising children.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As the Chancellor set out in the Summer Budget, this Government is making changes to tax credits to put welfare spending on a more sustainable path and to ensure that support is focused on those who need it most.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-07-13T13:26:34.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387786/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387786/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of tax credits on working families with children.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","5699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387787","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-14","<p>Since 2000, HMRC’s tobacco strategy has reduced the tax gap for cigarettes from 22% in 2000/01 to 10% in 2013/14, and the tax gap for hand-rolling tobacco from 61% to 39%. However, tobacco fraud remains a problem and HMRC works with other enforcement agencies to take action against those who participate in the fraud by smuggling and illegally manufacturing, distributing and selling non-UK duty paid product.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Sanctions against those selling tobacco without payment of duty include seizure of products, and cash, financial penalties and a maximum penalty of seven year’s imprisonment. On prosecution, HMRC can also apply for withdrawal of alcohol licenses and orders prohibiting the use of premises for the sale of tobacco for a period of up to 6 months. Additionally, as a result of coordinated activity with other enforcement agencies such as Trading Standards, the police and Immigration Enforcement officers, action can be taken on wider tobacco offences, such as under-age sales , and alcohol and vehicle licensing and immigration offences.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As reflected in the joint HMRC and Border Force refreshed strategy, ‘Tackling illicit tobacco: from leaf to light’, published on 24 March 2015, we need to get tougher on those involved in tobacco fraud through more effective use of sanctions. We have to deter participation and ensure that we come down harder on those who repeatedly offend.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>To this end, the refreshed strategy commits HMRC to working more across government at all points in the supply chain and to maximising the use and impact of all sanctions available. The published strategy also commits HMRC to undertaking an informal consultation in 2015. This will invite views from other departments and enforcement agencies, legitimate business affected by the fraud and public health organisations on how we can increase the effectiveness of existing sanctions and whether we need new sanctions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The strategy can be accessed on GOV.UK:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tackling-illicit-tobacco-from-leaf-to-light" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/tackling-illicit-tobacco-from-leaf-to-light</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-07-14T13:32:16.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387787/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387787/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Tobacco: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to tackle people who repeatedly sell cigarettes without paying duty.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","5732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387788","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>Phone charges are the responsibility of Ofcom and full details of costs can be found on their website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/phone/how-much-does-a-phone-call-really-cost/" target="_blank">http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/phone/how-much-does-a-phone-call-really-cost/</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The cost of calls to HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) helplines will vary depending on the call package that a customer has with their telephony provider.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-07-13T13:54:58.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387788/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387788/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387788/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-06","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much it costs per minute to telephone HM Revenue and Customs from a (a) landline and (b) mobile telephone; and if he will make it his policy to introduce free of charge telephone numbers for HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","5712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387789","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-09","<p>Details will be set out when the Housing Bill is published.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-09T13:46:31.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387789/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387789/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-06","Council Housing: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of council houses with two or more bedrooms that local authorities will be required to sell in the first five years after the implementation of the Housing Bill under the proposed provisions of that Bill.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","5697"
