"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387791","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Vacant Building Credit aims to promote housing development on brownfield sites, by allowing developers to offset the vacant building's floorspace that was due to be redeveloped for residential use against Section 106 affordable housing requirements.<br><br><br>We carried out a public consultation on these changes in March 2014 and as a result amended proposals to include buildings demolished for new development.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-13T14:10:31.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387791/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387791/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387791/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-06","Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect on the provision of residential development of the Vacant Building Credit; and if he will make a statement.","true","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","5702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387792","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my answer of 7 July, PQ 5357.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2015-07-09T15:15:55.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387792/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387792/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-06","Non-domestic Rates: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that Cumbria County Council and Cumbria's district councils receive more revenue raised from business rates.","false","Biography information for Sue Hayman","Workington","Sue Hayman","5637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387793","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-09","<p>As the my rt.hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Transport (Patrick McLoughlin) explained to the House in a statement on 25 June 2015, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 1067-1070, the electrification of the Transpennine route east of Stalybridge will be paused in order to ensure the programme overall delivers the maximum benefits and value to passengers. He reported to the Transport Committee in March 2015 that Transpennine electrification would be delayed to the 2020s and subsequently confirmed that the programme has been paused. It is right that my rt. hon. Friend has asked Network Rail to undertake a re-plan, and our Departments are in regular dialogue about such matters.</p><p> </p><p>Already, 32 miles of track from Liverpool to Manchester has been electrified, with the first electric service running earlier this year, replacing 2-car diesel trains with 4-car electric trains. The new Northern and Transpennine franchises starting next year will increase overall capacity by 36% by the end of 2019 and provide an extra 200 services each weekday, irrespective of when electrification east of Stalybridge is completed.</p><p> </p><p>I am therefore confident that the area will still benefit enormously from the investments being made.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Powerhouse is not purely a transport vision; it is an ambition to turn around decades of underperformance in the North, with commitments to science and technology, digital and innovation, culture and tourism, across the region, alongside devolving power to the major cities to give the North a powerful new voice.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","5570 ; 5571","2015-07-09T14:56:59.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387793/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387793/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-06","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 1 July 2015 to Question 4424, when his Department was first informed of the decision to delay the electrification of the Manchester to Leeds rail line.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","5687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387794","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Government is committed to devolving powers and budgets to maximise local economic growth. Building on the very successful City Deal programmes in the last Parliament, we have also been clear that we are open to discussing such proposals from all areas, towns and counties. We have been actively encouraging all areas to make compelling cases for increased powers and greater flexibility, and to demonstrate that there is strong governance over an appropriate geography, as well as the capacity and capability to deliver.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-07-13T14:40:51.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387794/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387794/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-06","Local Government: Peterborough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will extend the City Deals programme to Peterborough.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","5605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387795","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-08","<p>While we have removed change of use permitted development rights for pubs which are listed as Assets of Community Value, we would not want to impose unnecessary regulation where pubs are not viable or valued. This would not be proportionate and would add bureaucracy, cost and delay for business.</p><p> </p><p>Our current approach provides the right balance between protecting valued community pubs, but avoiding blanket regulation which would lead to more empty and boarded up buildings.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-08T15:43:09.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387795/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387795/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387795/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-06","Public Houses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will apply the restrictions on the conversion and demolition of pubs which are assets of community value to all pubs.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","5619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387796","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-15","<p>The village of Thrussington is connected to cabinet 1 of the Rearsby exchange. This cabinet is planned to be upgraded as part of Phase 1 of the Superfast Leicestershire project and expected to go live by the end of March 2016. The cabinet which serves the village’s homes and businesses is located in Thrussington village itself so many premises will be able to achieve superfast speeds of 24Mbps.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The village of Seagrave is served by cabinet 5 of the Sileby exchange. The village is planned to be covered as part of Phase 2 of the Superfast Leicestershire programme. Deployment is expected between late 2016 and autumn 2018. The local project team are working closely with BT and BDUK to accelerate the delivery.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the current coverage plans and timetable for homes and businesses in Leicestershire are available from the Superfast Leicestershire project team, although the details will be subject to change during the planning and survey stages. These can be found at: <a href="http://www.superfastleicestershire.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.superfastleicestershire.org.uk</a> which includes a 'When and Where' page linked to an interactive map.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-15T11:01:19.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387796/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387796/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387796/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Broadband: Charnwood","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 2 July 2015 to Question 4254, when the introduction of full superfast broadband coverage in (a) Seagrave and (b) Thrussington is planned to be completed.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","5622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387797","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-15","<p>Three projects supported through the Rural Community Broadband Fund, are being delivered through small suppliers, and eight contracts have been awarded by local bodies to suppliers other than BT to cover some or all of their project area as part of Phase 2 of the Government’s programme to provide superfast broadband to 95% of homes and businesses in the UK.<strong> </strong>The Rural Community Broadband Fund allowed communities to apply for funding to support locally delivered superfast broadband projects over 3 separate bidding rounds.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-15T11:03:14.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387797/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387797/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387797/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Broadband: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what role he plans small and medium-sized enterprises and smaller communications providers will have in delivering superfast broadband access to remote premises in his Department's superfast broadband roll-out programme.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","5667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387798","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-14","<p>No discussions have taken place with the BBC Trust on BBC Scotland funding. <br><br>The Charter Review is the time to consider all options around BBC. An announcement will be made in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-14T16:29:19.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387798/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387798/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387798/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","BBC Scotland: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with the BBC Trust on levels of funding for BBC Scotland.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","5675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387799","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Government recognises the important role that sport plays in all our lives and a Free-to-Air Listed Events regime has operated in the UK for many years. Taking into account the list, it is a commercial matter for the broadcasters to choose which sporting events to bid for.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-14T16:25:28.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387799/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387799/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387799/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Football: Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with broadcasters about free to view broadcast of international football matches involving the home nations.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","5741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387800","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-09","<p>The figure provided in the Freedom of Information response in May 2015 was based on an estimate for the works required to rectify the damage caused by the Libyan trainees. I refer the hon. Member to the answers to Question numbers 5131 and 2850 which provide the actual costs, based on the repairs that have already been completed and a more accurate survey of the outstanding work required.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-07-09T16:20:10.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387800/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387800/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387800/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-06","Libya: Military Bases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answers of 24 June 2015 and 1 July 2015 to Questions 5131 and 2850, what damage is covered by the figure of £472,283 given in a Freedom of Information response in May 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","5760"
